<P>
<B>Charter Schools in Action: What Have We Learned?</B><br>
 by Chester Finn, Bruno Manno, and Louann Bierlein
<P>
Hudson Institute<HR>

<P>
Finn, Manno and Bierlein report their findings from the first
year of a two-year Hudson Institute study of U.S. charter schools.
The report focuses on the schools' start-up problems, solutions
to those problems, and the policy environments in which such schools
are most apt to thrive or falter. Start-up problems, not surprisingly,
include financial burdens and regulatory and political hurdles.
Among the many recommendations the writers make are setting up
charter schools to be legal entities in their own right, giving
charter schools the same per pupil operating funds that conventional
public schools receive, and using the charter model to develop
ways of holding all public schools accountable for their results.
Hudson suggests that charter schools may be the most vibrant force
in American education today and notes that the current demand
for charter schools far outweighs the supply. 127 pp.  CONTACT:
Hudson Institute, Herman Kahn Center, P.O. Box 26-919, Indianapolis,
IN  46226, 317/545-1000, 317/545-9639, Internet <a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson/">http://www.hudson.org/hudson/</a>
