 by Chester Finn and Diane Ravitch
<P>
Hudson Institute<HR>

<P>
In the third annual report card on the progress of education reform
in the United States, the nation once again earned a grade of
&quot;C.&quot; The purpose of this report is to evaluate major
developments on several key refom fronts including course-taking,
achievement, standards, reinventing education, instruction, and
reinventing the federal role in education. Finn and Ravitch discover
rising enrollment figues in advanced math and science courses,
but disappointedly find that while more than three-fifths of high
school graduates now proceed directly to college, barely two-fifths
of them were in the academic track in high school. The study recommends
that schools continue to try to adhere to the strong academic
core that the National Commission on Excellence suggests. 66 pp.
