<title>September Insider -- Resource Bank -- Heritage</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"><br>
<h3>Resource Bank</h3><p>
From the September Edition of <i>The Insider</i><br>

<h2>Magazines & Journals</h2><p>

</center>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2><a href="/heritage/p_review/sept96/toc.html">September/October 1996</a>, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The cover story in this issue, <a href="/heritage/p_review/sept96/cal.html">&quot;Out of Order: Clinton's Court and its Assault on Justice,&quot;</a> by Steven Calabresi, details how many of the lower court judges, and both of the Supreme
Court Justices, appointed by Bill Clinton have replaced the Constitution
&quot;with radical and unpopular left-wing social policy.&quot;
Calabresi writes that Clinton appointees have written &quot;an
increasingly large number of opinions that are contemptuous of
the beliefs, values, and prerogatives of the American people as
well as of the democratic process itself.&quot; Other articles
in this issue examine the achievements of the 104</FONT><FONT SIZE=1>th</FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
Congress, how government regulations negatively affect women-owned
businesses, bilingual ballots, and a symposium on government's
role in saving the family. 64pp.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>The Madison Journal</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Vol. 4, No.3, James Madison Institute</FONT>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The theme of the summer issue of the journal is &quot;Breaking
the Rules-America's Moral and Cultural Choices.&quot; Media Critic
Michael Medved, Institute Vice President John Smith and Southeastern
Legal Foundation President Matthew Glavin are among the authors,
writing about Hollywood, teen pregnancies and the necessity of
a conservative ACLU, respectively. 20pp.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>Philanthropy</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Summer 1996, Philanthropy Roundtable</FONT>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>This issue features three articles on the affect
that religious organizations can have in the delivery of social
services. The articles-&quot;Should Churches Get into Welfare
Refrom?&quot;; &quot;Liberty and Learning-Each Leaning on the
Other&quot;; and &quot;Should Voluntary Groups Seek Government
Funding?&quot;-examine the positive role that faith-based organizations
can have, while cautioning that there can be difficulties. 30pp.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>Reason</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>October 1996, Reason Foundation</FONT>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Topics include: how the FEC is crushing free speech;
why airline safety should be depoliticized; Newt Gingrich's environmental
policy; and Singapore's &quot;'free market.'&quot; Also in this
issue is an article by Silicon Valley CEO T.J. Rodgers that demonstrates
that the morality of capitalism and a responsibility to shareholders
dictate that arbitrarily placing racial or gender quotas on corporate
boards is not only fundamentally wrong, but also an &quot;immoral&quot;
act. 66pp. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>Rutherford</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Vol. 5, No. 6, Rutherford Institute</FONT>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The focus this month is on the capital punishment.
Leigh Dingerson outlines the history of capital punishment in
the United States and address the question of how justice can
be served. Another article looks at the tradition of executions
in the Western world, reviews Dead Man Walking, and examines artists'
treatments of the theme of capital punishment. 27pp.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>Headway</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>August 1996, Richberg Communications</FONT>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The cover story, &quot;Media Code Words,&quot; examines
how the media manipulates Americans with the words that they use.
Other articles include: &quot;Media too Often Meddle with Political
System&quot;; &quot;Media's Social Agenda Out of Touch with Average
Americans&quot;; and &quot;Black Republicans' Image Distorted
by Media.&quot; Among the other topics in the magazine are the
Children's Defense Fund, racial relationships, and gay marriages.
38pp.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>Priorities</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Vol. 8, No. 2, American Council on Science and Health</FONT>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>This special issue of <I>Priorities</I> reveals &quot;the
stark contrast between the public health challenges we face today
and those we confronted in the early part of this century.&quot;
Articles attempt to address and answer the question where do Americans
draw the line between government involvement, and individual choice
and personal freedom, when behavior, and not micro-organisms,
are the targets of public health campaigns? The issue also includes
a &quot;Point/Counterpoint&quot; column on FDA regulation of medical
devices. 48pp.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
