<a href="/heritage/library/categories/theory/lect567.html">Liberating People for Self-Government, </a>by Stephen Goldsmith<p>
<i>Lecture</i> No. 567, The Heritage Foundation<p>
In this speech given at The Heritage Foundation's Resource Bank Annual Meeting, Indianapolis Mayor Stephen Goldsmith puts forth ways in which Americans can liberate themselves for self-government. He begins his speech by discussing his experience as mayor and how he eschewed the public policy trends of the last thirty years of continuously raising taxes and establishing social programs and control mechanisms to solve the city's problems. As mayor, he has contracted out several city services, set up incentives for social workers to place welfare recipients in jobs, connected kids in tough neighborhodds to their local churches, fought for school choice, and overall, allowed flexibility and innovation in the delivery of public services. Goldsmith calls for devolution, but warns that it will not be successful unless it leads to a market-based system for providing government services. The system has to recognize that "the way to create true value is to let citizens and taxpayers make decisons that are in their own best interests." 5pp.  CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a>
<p>
<b>Understanding the Christian Right, </b>by John C. Green<p>
American Jewish Committee<p>
The political movement that has come to be known as the "Christian Right" is a major player in American politics, writes, John C. Green, Professor of Political Science and Director of the Ray C. Bliss Institute of Applied Politics at the University of Akron. Green, provides an neutral assesment of the Christian Right in religious and political terms. He includes chapters entitiled: The Elements of the Christian Right; Understanding Evangelical Protestantism; Antecedents of the Christian Right; The Rise of the "New" Christian Right; The Contemporary Christian Right; The Christian Right and the Jews; The impact of the Christian Right; and Prospects for the Christian Right.  43pp.  CONTACT. The American Jewish Committee, 165 East 56 Street, New York, NY 10022-2746.
<p>
<b>Initiative and Referendum in Pennsylvania,</b> by Charles E. Greenwalt II<p>
Commonwealth Foundation<p>
The process of "direct democracy," by way of initiatives and referendum, has fallen short of what reformers had in mind because of its extreme vulnerability to corruption. The question is, writes Charles Greenwalt, Senior Policy Associate at The Commonwealth Foundation, should Pennsylvania join the list of 24 states (and the District of Columbia) that have adopted procedures for statewide initiatives and the 25 states (and the District) that have adopted statewide referendum? Some of the major opposition relates to issues involving "finances," which would only allow those special interest groups with a good financial backing to get their issues on the ballot. Another problem the opposition raises is the belief of a 'complexity' of issues', which argues that the average or even slightly above average citizen would not really understand what he/she was voting on because the topics are too complex for their understanding. Proponents see this "direct" process as a must and point to the Pennsylvania Constitution, which says that the power and right to make laws ultimately rests with the citizentry. In addition, proponents of initiative and referendum believe that a higher voter turnout that develop and provide additional checks on lawmakers. Either way, concludes Greenwalt, what will work for one state may not work for another, thus each state must decide individually if the process of initiative and referendum outweighs the cost of corruption. 40pp.  CONTACT: The Commonwealth Foundation for Public Policy Alternatives, 3544 North Progress Avenue, Suite 101, Harrisburg, PA  17110, 717/671-1901, fax 717/671-1905.
<p>
<b>Setting Limits: The Truth About Why Congress Defeated the Term Limits and Balanced Budget Amendments in 1995, </b>by Cleta Deatherage Mitchell<p>
Americans Back in Charge<p>
Cleta Deatherage Mitchell argues that the American people instinctively know that term limits will permanently limit the time that politicians can spend in Washington and further that a balanced budget amendment will permanently limit money that politicians in Washington can spend. Moreover, these amendments will restore to the Constitution the notion of a finite federal government, something that was implicit in the design of the government and understood by the Founders as an essential part of the system they created. In addition, Mitchell identifies and outlines the motivations of the obstructionists in Congress who blocked these reforms. 95pp.  CONTACT. Americans Back in Charge, 900 2nd Street, N.E., Suite 200A. Washington, DC 20002, 202/371-0450, fax 202/371-0210, e-mail <a href="mailto: 72242.651@compuserve.com">72242.651@compuserve.com.</a>
<p>
<b>U.S. Term Limits</b><p>
Recent Publications<p><ul>
<p><li><b>The Changing Legislature: Term Limits and the Oregon Experience,</b> by Tom Holt, <i>Term Limits Outlook Series</i> Vol. V, No. 2. This study, by Tom Holt, illustrates that the 1992 Oregon term limit law has already effected the legislature even though it will not force anyone from office until 1998. The political culture has become increasingly agenda oriented, according to Holt, which has resulted in more frequent and quicker votes on policy changes with less reliance on the seniority system.  15 pp. 

<p><li><b>Assembly Transformed: The Early Effects of Term Limits in Arkansas,</b> by Donald V. Weatherman,  <i>Term Limits Outlook Series</i> Vol. IV, No. 5. Donald Weatherman, Professor of Political Philosophy at Lyon College, examines the early effects of term limits in Arkansas. Term limits were upheld by the Arkansas Supreme Court in 1993. Since then, observes Weatherman, numerous changes have already occurred in both the seniority structure of the Assembly and the substance of legislation. Weatherman also reports that more "good government bills" have come to the floor than during any other recent session of the legislature. Weatherman concludes by writing that the new frontier of the term limits movement will be at the county government level, where elected officials are the most entrenched. 12pp. CONTACT: U.S. Term Limits, 1511 K Street, N.W., Suite 540, Washington, DC 20005, 800/733-6440, fax 202/393-6434.
</ul>
