<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>NATIONAL SECURITY <BR>
&AMP; FOREIGN POLICY</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/natsec/bg1074.html">
Defending America: Ending America's Vulnerability to Ballistic Missiles:</a>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
An Update by the Missile Defense Study Team ("Team B")</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 1074, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3>In 1995, The Heritage Foundation created a Missile Defense Study Team, 
Team B, to look at the growing threat of ballistic missiles armed with weapons of mass 
destruction and  produced a report that recommended timely, affordable and technically
sound responses to a missile threat in the form of a missile defense system. This update
offers several new recommendations to adjust to the delays and negative developments
that have characterized the missile defense program in the past year including: <br>
<ol><li>the U.S. Senate should seek ways to remove the obstacles to effective missile
defenses posed by the ABM Treaty, including possible withdrawal from the treaty; <li>
Congress should forego development of ground-based systems for national missile 
defense and accelerate deployment of sea-based, wide-area defenses; <li>Congress
should accelerate the deployment of space-based sensors to enhance the effectiveness 
of both theater and national missile defense; <li>Congress should direct the Air Force 
to develop follow-on space-based defenses to begin deployment early in the next decade; 
<li>Congress should ensure that the Ballistic Missile Defense Office develops an integrated,
but open, architecture for battle management, command, control, and communications to 
support missile defense systems.</ol>14 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage 
Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 
202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/forpol/asc139.html">
China's Threats to Taiwan Challenges U.S. Leadership in Asia,</a> <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Richard Fisher</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Asian Studies Center Backgrounder</FONT></I>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No. 139, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<p>
Richard Fisher, Senior Policy Analyst at the Heritage Foundation, believes that deterring conflict in the 
Taiwan Strait is the most important challenge for American foreign policy in early 1996. China has 
militarily intimidated the emerging democratic system of Taiwan ever since the Republic of Chinas 
President, Lee Tenghui, visited the United States in June of 1995. According to Fisher, what is at stake in 
Taiwan is not only peace and stability in the region, but the viability of democracy in Taiwan. Since 1987 
the Republic of China has sought democratic political reforms that will soon make Taiwan a democracy.  
12 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., 
Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<a name="commerce"</a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<center><font size=5>COMMERCE, INFRASTRUCTURE
& REGULATION</font></center>

<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/regulation/tp11.html">
A Policy Maker's Guide to Deregulation Telecommunications Part 6: A Free-Market
Future for Spectrum</a>,<BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Adam Thierer</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Heritage Talking Points</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No.10, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
Adam Thierer, Alex C. Walker Fellow in Economic Policy at The Heritage Foundation, traces 
the history of government regulation of the electromagnetic wireless spectrum and how it relates 
to the recent Telecommunications Bill, including the false assumptions about the spectrum that 
have been used to justify continued government regulation and infringement of First Amendment 
rights. Thierer calls for the following steps to be taken to ensure meaningful free market reforms:
<br><ol><li>provide fully flexible, perpetual property rights in spectrum; <li>government agencies 
responsible for managing the spectrum should be required to allocate and auction off as much of 
the spectrum as possible;<li>redefine (or define for the first time) the &quot;public interest&quot; 
standard and ensure thatFirst Amendment protections are accorded equally to all media; and <li>
transfer all remaining spectrum authority from the governing federal agencies to the courts, private 
entities, and an independent body.</ol>21 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage 
Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, 

fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<B><font size=3>Regulation's Trillion-Dollar Drag on Productivity,</FONT></B>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Richard Vedder</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Policy Brief </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
165, Center for the Study of American Business<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
This report by Richard Vedder, John M. Olin Visiting Professor of Labor Economics and Public Policy at 
the Center for the Study of American Business, argues that the U.S. GDP today might be 20 percent higher 
if the regulatory buildup that began in the Johnson Administration had not occured. According to his 
analysis, if regulatory activity remained at 1963 levels, the 1993 U.S. GDP would have been about $7.6 
trillion instead of $6.3 trillion. Vedder notes that regulation imposes direct costs, requiring businesses to 
commit resources to implement governmental mandates. He concludes by writing that while some 
regulations are necessary, such as those on food and drugs, other regualtions have expanded without fully 
considering the costs and consequences of such action. 13 pp. CONTACT: Center for the Study of 
American Business, Washington University, Campus Box 1208, St. Louis, MO 63130-4899, 314/935-
5630, fax 314/935-5688.<p>

<B><font size=3>Government Regulation of Medium-Sized Business, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Murray Weidenbaum</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Contermpoary Issues</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No.77, Center for the Study of American Business <BR></FONT>
<P>
Chairman of Center for the Study of American Business Murray Weidenbaum argues that nearly all of the 
attention in public policy discussions and legislation aimed at reducing the regulatory burden on business is 
focused on either very large enterprises or very small businesses. According to Weidenbaum, medium 
sized firms do not benefit from the protections provided to small businesses or the economies of scale 
generated by large businesses. Fortune 500 companies fill out basically the same forms and meet the same 
requirements as medium-sized firms. Therefore, the cost of complying with regulation is a higher percent 
of sales for the medium-sized firms than for larger ones. Weidenbaum shows that Congress has responded 
to the issue of uneven distribution of regulatory burdens in the predictable manner. Instead of reducing the 
burden of regulation, it has arbitrarily exempted companies of different sizes. He gives as an example, a 
series of federal regulations that take effect when a company hires its 50th employee. Because of this, some 
small firms are reluctant to expand. Weidenbaum concludes by recommending that Congress significantly 
reform and reduce regulation on business. CONTACT: Center for the Study of American Business, 
Washington University, Campus Box 1208, St. Louis, MO 63130-4899, 314/935-5630, fax 314/935-5688.<p>


<B><font size=3>Federal Power: The Case for Privatizing Electricity, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Douglas Houston</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
Reason Foundation</FONT>
<P>
The Tennessee Valley Authority (TVA) and the five power marketing administrations (PMAs) are the 
entities that make the federal government the nations largest producer of electric power. According to 
Douglas Houston, Professor of Business Economics at the University of Kansas, these electricity 
businesses, along with other federally subsidized cooperatives and municipal utilities, are inefficient, 
poorly managed and at risk in the environment of electricity competition. Houston argues that privatizing 
federal electricity and ending current subsidies would have the following benefits:<br><ol><li>
the sale of federal power enterprises would raise $15-30 billion to reduce the national debt; <li>$7-10 billion in direct subsidies 
to government-owned utilities and cooperatives would end; <li> privatization would lead to improved 
performance and efficiency and eliminate the political interference in management and investment 
decisions that government owned utilities have to face; and <li> putting the transmission grids of the TVA 
and the PMAs into the emerging competitive market would promote efficiency and lower prices for 
consumers.</ol> Overall, Houston concludes that ending electricity subsidies and privatizing is a win-win 
situation. 36 pp. CONTACT: Reason Foundation, 3415 S. Sepulveda Blvd., Suite 400, Los Angeles, CA  
90034, 310/391-2245, fax 310/391-4395.<p>

<B><font size=3>Private Tollways for Wisconsin, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Robert Poole</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Report Vol. 9,</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No.2, Research Institute<BR></FONT>
<P>
Robert Poole, President of the Reason Foundation, writes that although Wisconsin has an excellent 
highway system, the majority of the states major highways will require reconstruction during the next 25 
years. Complicating matters, the Wisconsin Department of Transportation projects that current funding 
sources will fall $8.9 billion short of paying for the needed maintenance. As a solution to the shortfall, 
Poole proposes a public-private partnership to build toll roads in the state highway system. Poole believes 
that such a partnership has many benefits, including: highway innovations, new funding sources, risk 
transfer, new tax revenue, reduced operating costs, better-maintained roads, greater safety levels, 
congestion relief. Potential problems include: loss of public control, bankruptcy, labor issues and higher 
financing costs. Poole concludes with a description of what steps should be taken to bring about toll roads 
as a solution to Wisconsins highway maintenance problems including: a detailed feasability study and 
state and federal legislation to provide the adequate legal framework. 27 pp. CONTACT: Wisconsin Policy 
Research Institute, 3107 N. Shepard Ave., Milwaukee, WI  53211, 414/963-0600, fax 414/963-4230.<p>

<B><font size=3>The Transprotation Lobby: The Politics of Highway and Transit, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Peter Samuel</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Capital Research Center
</FONT>
<P>
According Transportation expert Peter Samuel, taxpayers are the biggest losers in American transportation 
policy. Samuel writes that although transportation policy is in need of reform in order to pay for its massive 
costs and to best serve the interests of commuters, entrenched interests stand in the way of meaningful 
reform. Those interests that directly influence transportation policy in Washington include: highway 
construction companies seeking more federally funded projects; social engineers seeking transit systems 
that conform to their ideals; and automobile organizations, such as AAA, who fight against such policy 
innovations as private toll roads that they feel threaten travel and commerce. Samuel illustrates the 
historical development of the transportation lobbies into what they are today and provides a history of 
government highway and transportation policy. Samuel concludes his report by saying that the first step of 
achieving reform is to realize that government monopoly in roads is not the solution. New technology and 
privatization are the answer, although it will entail taking on the entrench transportation lobbying forces 
inside the Beltway. 5 pp. CONTACT: Capital Research Center, 727 15th St., NW, 8th Floor, Washington, 
DC  20005, 202/393-2600, fax 202/393-2626.<p>


<B><font size=3>Race & Income in Pittsburgh: A Statistical Portrait, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Jerry Bowyer</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Allegheny Institute</FONT>
<P>
Jerry Bowyer, President of the Allegheny Institute, criticizes a study prepared last year in the University of 
Pittsburghs &quot;Economic Benchmarks&quot; report, as well as other studies that suggest that racial prejudice is 
doing severe harm to the economic conditions of blacks, and that the city of Pittsburgh is worse in this 
regard than the rest of the nation. Bowyer provides evidence that economic disparity can almost entirely be 
attributed to a combination of distinct demographic patterns and behavioral factors within the black 
community and not racial prejudice. He notes that the University of Pittsburgh study does not take into 
account such factors as family structure and high school and college drop out rates. The researchers instead 
just measure disparity, and on this issue it is not even complete. Bowyer argues that it is irresponsible to 
report racial income disparity figures in a racially charged urban atmosphere, where the figures are likely to 
be misinterpreted, unless steps are taken to make sure that the results are properly understood. Bowyer 
concludes that these studies, because of their omissions, are more likely to further economic disparities 
than promote problemsolving. CONTACT: Allegheny Institute for Public Policy, Suite 612, 7 Parkway 
Center, Pittsburgh, PA 15220-3703, 412/937-4526, fax 412/928-1501.<p>

<B><font size=3>What is Happening to Americans' Income?, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Michael Cox and Beverly Fox</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Policy Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No.138, National Center for Policy Analysis<BR></FONT>
<P>
Michael Cox and Beverly Fox, of the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas, explore why media reports paint a 
bleak picture of the average American workers prospects today, despite very positive economic indicators 
suggesting that the economy is thriving. After examining several different economic trends, the authors 
conclude that they are no cause for alarm. An examination of the dataan increase in employee benefits, a 
decline in median household or family size, and a shortening in the average workweekprovides a fairly 
bright picture of Americans improving living standards. According to Fox and Cox, from the perspective 
of the most long term and broadest economic aggregates, per capita real GDP and consumption, recent 
gains for Americans are on par with overall historical gains. 11 pp. CONTACT: National Center for Policy 
Analysis, 12655 N. Central Expy., Suite 720, Dallas, TX  75243-1739, 214/386-6272, fax 214/386-0924, 
Internet	 <a href="http://www.shoponline.com/ncpa">http://www.shoponline.com/ncpa</a><p>

<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/trade/bg1070.html">Fulfilling the Promise of NAFTA: A New Strategy for U.S.-Mexican Relations, 
</a></FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
John Sweeney</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No.1070, The Heritage Foundation<BR></FONT>
<P>
John Sweeney, Policy Analyst at the Heritage Foundation, argues that the Clinton Administration has 
retreated from promoting the expansion of free trade in the Western hemisphere. Sweeney points out that 
during the past year the President has reneged on his pledge to include Chile in NAFTA by 1996, and the 
that Administration has violated key provisions of the treaty. Sweeney calls for several steps to be taken by 
the President to correct the current drift away from free trade:<br><ol><li>the U.S. should fulfill all of its NAFTA 
obligations on schedule; <li> NAFTA should be expanded; <li> Mexico should be encouraged to adopt a 
currency board; <li> the Administration should offer to negotiate forgiveness of Mexicos public sector 
foreign debt; and <li> the Administration should offer to negotiate a law enforcement agreement with 
Mexico to deal with the growing problem of international organized crime and drug trafficking.</ol> Sweeney 
also proposes a free-market solution for Mexican monetary troubles, writing that Clintons $50 billion 
bailout of Mexico has not only failed to stop the trend of devaluation, depression and eventual default, it 
also ignored principles of free-trade. 14 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 
Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail 
<a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<P>
<a name="taxation"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>TAXATION &AMP; BUDGET</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/bg1073.html">Getting the Federal Budget Process Back on Track,</a>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Ronald Utt</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
1073, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
Ronald Utt, Visiting Fellow at The Heritage Foundation, suggests a strategy for Congress to get its budget 
and policy goals back on track. He argues that if Congress hopes to enact its legislative agenda this year, it 
should adopt a two-year budget and break down appropriations bills into more manageable pieces of 
legislation, noting that Clintons 1997 budget is already out, even though all the appropriations for 1996 
have yet to be passed. Utt also argues that Congress should not use last years strategy of waiting until the 
end of the year to present the president with an all-or-nothing appropriations bill. This strategy backfired 
and allowed President Clinton to avoid an open debate on the issue. If the appropriations process is broken 
down into smaller bills, contends Utt, Congress can directly debate policy on a program-by-program basis. 
This would expose the negative aspects of the Presidents defense of the status quo. Utt points out that the 
same strategy can be used on entitlement programs such as Medicare, Medicaid and welfare. Reforms in 
these programs were vetoed at once when combined in one huge reconciliation bill. If they were free 
standing measures, however, there would be a better chance of conducting a substantive policy debate. 7 
pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., 
Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/bg1071.html">Clinton's FY Budget: The Era of Big Government Lives On,</a> 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Scott Hodge</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
1071, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
Scott Hodge, Grover M. Herman Fellow in Federal Budgetary Affairs at The Heritage Foundation, 
illustrates that the Clinton Administration is still for big government, despite claims to the contrary. Hodge 
finds that the FY 1997 Clinton budget continues the era of big government in several ways: it increases 
federal spending by $361 billion over the next seven years and hikes tax revenue by $526 billion; it spends 
a total of $12.16 trillion over the next seven years, or $306 billion more than the vetoed Balance Budget 
Act of 1995$3,155 more for every household in America; it raises a total of $11.4 trillion in tax revenues 
over seven years, $187 billion more than the BBA, and $1,927 more in taxes for every household in 
America; it allows $119 billion more deficit spending through 2002 than the BBA, which is equivalent to 
passing along $1,227 per household in debt to the next generation of America workers; it fails to eliminate a 
single program of any significance; it fails to eliminate even one Cabinet-level agency; it increases 
entitlement spending by $365 billion over the next seven years while failing to save Medicare from 
bankruptcy, end welfare as we know it, or protect states from exploding costs of Medicaid; and it spends 
$111 billion more in spending on programs that have failed or become obsolete, that duplicate others, or 
that should be transferred to state and local government control. 13 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, 
The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, 
fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/fyi90.html">How the Armey Shelby Flat Tax Would Affect the Middle Class,</a> 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
William Beach and Dan Mitchell</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>F.Y.I.</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
90, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
The 17 percent flat tax plan sponsored by House Majority Leader, Dick Armey, and Sen. Richard Shelby, 
shows no increase in the taxes paid by the vast majority of middle-class Americans when compared with 
their current tax burden, according to William Beach, Visiting Fellow in Tax Analysis, and Dan Mitchell, 
Heritage McKenna Senior Fellow in Political Economy. In fact, a 17percent  flat tax, on average, would 
lower taxes on all income groups. Based on IRS income-tax files for 1991, under a 17 percent flat tax, 
households with less than $15,000 per year in taxable income will experience a nearly 50 percent drop in 
their tax burden. Moreover, About 24 million families who pay federal income taxes now will pay no 
federal income taxes under the fully implemented Armey-Shelby flat tax, the analysts say, and nearly 
everyone else below $30,000 in taxable income will see their taxes fall. According to Beach and Mitchell, 
lower taxes will not mean higher deficits. The loss in individual income tax revenue under the Armey-
Shelby plan will be offset by increased revenue from middle-sized and big businesses. 7 pp. CONTACT: 
Chris OScannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/fyi85.html">Why Liberals Should Support the Flat Tax,</a></font></b>

by Dan Mitchell
<p>
<I><font size=3>F.Y.I.</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
85, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
Dan Mitchell, McKenna Senior Fellow in Political Economy at the Heritage Foundation, points out that 
polls show that workers, investors, savers, entrepreneurs, farmers, small business owners, and the elderly 
are among the groups of Americans drawn to the flat-tax because they feel that they will pay less. He then 
gives and elaborates on eight reasons why another group, liberals, should support the flat tax:<br><ol><li>the key 
philosophical principle of the flat tax is equality; <li> lower rates result in the rich shouldering more of the 
tax burden; <li>current deductions disproportionately benefit the wealthy and others able to exploit 
loopholes; <li>radically simplifying the code with a flat tax will help end the corrupting effect of tax 
lobbyists; <li>because of a generous family-based allowance, the poor are shielded from the income tax 
burden; <li>the flat tax will boost wages and income for lower-income and middle-income workers; <li>a 
pro-growth tax system will reduce the budget deficit; and <li>lower-income and middle-income taxpayers 
will enjoy a more financially secure retirement.</ol> Mitchell ends by including several quotes supporting a flat 
tax from unlikely sources, such as The Washington Post, The Nation, Leon Panetta, and The New York 
Times. 10 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., 
Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<B><font size=3>Tax Reform's "Third Rail": Mortgage Interest, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Bruce Bartlett</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Policy Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No.139, National Center for Policy Analysis</FONT>
<P>
Bruce Bartlett, Senior Fellow at the Alexis de Toqueville Institution, illustrates how the mortgage interest 
deduction has become the untouchable &quot;third rail&quot; in any discussion of a flat tax. This is despite the fact 
that homeowners would gain more from a flat-rate tax than they would lose if the mortgage deduction was 
taken away. Nonetheless, Bartlett points out, realtors have declared &quot;war&quot; against the flat tax. He 
dismantles the key study issued by the National Association of Realtors by DRI/McGraw-Hill, a private 
economic consulting firm, that concludes the Armey flat tax proposal would cause housing prices to 
collapse from the elimination of the mortgage interest deduction. According to Bartlett, not only would 
mortgage rates fall by about 18 percent as soon as the flat tax takes effect,  in the unlikely event that a flat 
tax caused housing prices to fall, the decline would only be temporary. Furthermore, the flat tax would benefit homeowners by eliminating the capital 
gains tax. 9 pp. CONTACT: National Center for Policy Analysis, 12655 N. Central Expy., Suite 720, 
Dallas, TX  75243-1739, 214/386-6272, fax 214/386-0924, Internet
<a href="http://www.shoponline.com/ncpa">http://www.shoponline.com/ncpa</a><p>

<B><font size=3>Tax Funded Politics 
</FONT></B>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Alternatives in Philanthropy,</FONT></I>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">The Capital Research Center</FONT>
<P>
This issue features two articles examining grants made by the Center for Disease Control and the National 
Cancer Institute to nonprofit anti-smoking organizations. The articles discuss how tax dollars granted for 
disease research and public health education have been funneled into political advocacy. James Bennett, 
Professor of Economics at George Mason University, looks at the National Cancer Institutes illegal use of 
federal funds to promote a Colorado ballot initiative to raise the states tobacco tax. He unveils front 
groups created to provide a smokescreen for lobbying; state bureaucrats using state offices to facilitate 
lobbying; and the selling of positions of authority. In the other article Thomas DiLorenzo, Senior Fellow at 
the Capital Research Center, shows that the Center for Disease Control (CDC) is heavily involved in 
funding political advocacy. He centers on a $30,000 grant the CDC awarded to the American Lung 
Associations (ALA) May 1993 conference, Seize the Initiative: A National Training Conference for 
Increasing Tobacco Excise Taxes Through Initiated Acts. DiLorenzo states that CDC diverted from its 
mission of conducting disease research and educating the public about health issues to teaching political 
organizing and lobbying techniques, a blatantly illegal use of tax money. 8 pp. CONTACT: Capital 
Research Center, 727 15th St., NW, 8th Floor, Washington, DC  20005, 202/393-2600, fax 202/393-2626.<p>


<B><font size=3>Capital Crimes: Political Centers as Parasite Economies, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Richard Vedder</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Policy Analysis</FONT></i><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
250, Cato Institute</FONT>
<P>
Richard Vedder, Professor of Economics at Ohio University, argues that capital cities in the United States 
are &quot;parasite economies&quot; which drain resources from surrounding areas. According to Vedder, lawyers, 
lobbyists, legislators, bureaucrats, and government contractors take productive resources from the average 
taxpayer to fill their own pockets. Vedder uses statistical comparisons of factors such as income, 
population change, unemployment, and working conditions to illustrate how capital cities &quot;siphon&quot;wealth 
from other areas. He shows that the average annual pay for workers in the Washington D.C. area exceeds 
the national average by 48 percent. Furthermore, the per capita income in the capital cities of the poorest 
states are about 17 percent above the state averages. Vedder concludes by saying that it is not a coincidence 
that a majority of the state capitals that have gained the most in relative affluence are in the poorest states. 
According to Vedder, this shows that the taxes that finance affluent capitals crowd out private-sector 
activity that is usually more efficient and productive than government activity. 23 pp. CONTACT: Cato 
Institute, 1000 Massachusetts Ave., NW, Washington, DC  20001, 202/842-0200, fax 202/842-3490, e-
mail gregory@cato.org, Internet <a href="http:// www.cato.org">http://www.cato.org</a><p>

<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/govern/bg1069.html">Top Ten Political Slush Funds,</a>  
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Charles Griffin</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
1069, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
Charles Griffin, former Deputy Director of the Government Integrity Project at the Heritage Foundation, 
examines slush funds in the federal government budget that can be used to subsidize the lobbying and 
political activities of special-interest groups. He shows that the agendas of these tax-subsidized groups tend 
toward bigger government, more spending, and increased regulation. Griffin calls for the elimination of 
such slush funds. He examines each one and illustrates how they use the millions in federal funding to 
lobby for their special interests. Griffin concludes by calling for an end to federally subsidized political 
activism. 14 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, 
N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>


<a name="health"</a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<center><font size=5>Health & Welfare</font></center><p>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/healthwel/fyi89.html">Key Changes Needed in the Governors' Medicaid Proposal,</a> 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
<a href="/heritage/staff/liu.htm">John Liu</a></FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>F.Y.I.</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
89, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
According to Heritage Health Care Policy Analyst John Lui, the National Governors Associations 
Medicaid reform plan ignores many of the biggest problems of the current system. He writes that the 
highly touted Medicaid reform plan drafted by the governors contains many needed reforms, but unless a 
final bill differs sharply in some critical details, the plan will be a disaster. The governors plan claims to 
scrap the Medicaid entitlement in favor of a system of block grants to the states, yet preserves a long list of 
benefits that must be provided to a large, entitled population. In addition, since the governors decision to 
guarentee Medicaid coverage to so many people will impose heavy burdens on state budgets, they also 
included an &quot;umbrella insurance&quot; provision that, in effect, &quot;entitles&quot; states to federal money. If states 
experience an unanticipated rise in the number of people eligible for Medicaid, the federal government 
would bear the cost, which almost certainly would increase the federal deficit. Liu recommends that 
Congress make the following changes to the governors plan:<br><ol><li>sharply limit the guaranteed populations 
and benefits of the entitlement; and <li>the umbrella should be a budgeted fund appropriated each year, not 
an entitlement to states.</ol> 3 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 
Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail 
<a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/healthwel/bg1075.html">Welfare Reform Fraud Once Again: Examining the NGA Welfare Plan,</a> 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
<a href="/heritage/staff/rector.htm">Robert Rector</a></FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
1075, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
Robert Rector, Senior Policy Analyst at the Heritage Foundation, criticizes the National Governors 
Associations welfare reform proposal for entirely ignoring the No. 1 problem that experts say perpetuates 
the welfare culture, illegitimacy. He also points out that the NGA plan repudiates most of the key elements 
of the Contract with America. The Contracts welfare reform was based on three themes: a national goal of 
reducing illegitimacy; national work requirements; and greater flexibility to state governments. The NGA 
plan, according to Rector, does not contain the first two principles of reform. Rector argues that the NGA 
plan is flawed in four aspects: <li>it abandons the welfare reform goal of reducing illegitimacy; <li>it 
eliminates all work requirements for AFDC recipients; <li>it has a pervasive anti-marriage bias; and <li>it 
embodies the Clinton Administrations &quot;reform&quot; structure, which penalizes states that pursue efficient plans.</ul> Rector concludes that bogus reforms, such as the NGA proposal, reduce public pressure for change 
and thereby helps encourage the existing system. 12 pp. CONTACT: Chris OScannlain, The Heritage 
Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-
0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/healthwel/cb22.html">The Costs to the States of Not Fundamentally reforming Medicaid</a> 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
<a href="/heritage/staff/beach.htm">William Beach</a></FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Committee Brief</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
22, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
William Beach, Heritage Foundation Visiting Fellow in Tax Analysis, warns that the debate between 
Congress and the President on reforming Medicaid has not paid enough attention to the effect of the 
program on state finances. He writes that if significant reforms in Medicaid are not enacted, state 
governments will face a major increase in spending and a heavy increase in the proportion of their 
projected revenues that they must dedicate to the program. Beach shows that the cost of Medicaid to the 
federal government has grown at double-digit rates in recent years. Congressional Budget Office 
projections show annual federal Medicaid costs doubling by the year 2002. According to Beach there will 
be an estimated shift of $47.4 billion in mandated Medicaid spending from the federal government to state 
governments over the next seven years. He believes that states will respond in one of three ways:<br><ol><li>by 
enacting dramatic tax increases; <li>by reducing state spending on education, infrastructure, law 
enforcement, and other important state functions; or <li>by some combination of the first two.</ol> The National 
Association of State Budget Officers claims that Medicaid spending has already doubled from 
approximately 10 percent to 20 percent as a share of overall state spending since 1987. 5 pp. CONTACT: 
Chris OScannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-
4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org.</a><p>

<B><font size=3>Giving Credit Where Credit is Due: A New Approach to Welfare Funding , 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
James Angelini, William O'Brien &amp; David Tuerck</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3BHI Polich Study></FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">The
Beacon Hill Institute</FONT>
<P>
David Tuerck, Executive Director of the Beacon Hill Institute, James Angelini, Professor of Accounting 
and Taxation at Suffolk University, and William OBrien, Resident Scholar at the Beacon Hill Institute, 
argue that the method by which the government funds welfare programs causes the taxpayer to have no 
incentive to take interest in how his money is spent. The taxpayer (who is a potential donor to charitable, 
nonprofit organizations) has no clear idea of how much of his tax money makes it to a welfare recipient, so 
he has no control over the tax dollar and therefore, argue Angelini, OBrien, and Tuerck, over the behavior 
of the welfare recipient. The authors propose that the same funds that now directly flow into government 
offices can instead flow into private charitable organizations. The tax credit they propose will allow 
taxpayers to deduct 100% of their contributions to eligible charities to up to 25% of their federal tax 
liability. This gives the taxpayer/donor control over where his dollar is spent. Angelini, OBrien, and 
Tuerck predict that such a tax credit will cause new organizations to respond to the increased opportunities 
presented to them. They conclude that competition will lead to efficiency and charitable organizations will 
be more innovative and successful than government in providing social services. 165 pp. CONTACT: 
Beacon Hill Institute for Public Policy Research, Suffolk University, 8 Ashburton Place, Boston, MA  
02108, 617/573-8750, fax 617/720-4272.<p>

<a name="educate"</a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<center><font size=5>EDUCATION</font></center>
<p>
<B><font size=3> The Fiscal Impact of NEA's Legislative Agenda, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
John Berthoud</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>The Alexis De Toqueville Institution</FONT></I>
<P>
This study, by John Berthoud, Vice President of the Alexis de Toqueville Institution, reveals that if every 
item in the National Education Associations (NEA) Legislative Program for the 104th Congress were 
enacted, federal spending would increase by at least $702 billion annually. The study uses data on 
legislative proposals compiled by the National Taxpayers Union Foundation in their BillTally tracking 
system. The spending estimates for the different proposals come from non-partisan sources such as the 
Congressional Budget Office. One of the findings in this report is that the NEAs spending priorities are 
heavily skewed towards elderly Americans, despite NEAs claim that it is an educational organization with 
a primary focus on schools and children. The study finds that for each dollar in new spending on children 
and education that the NEA proposes (over $24 billion annually), it advocates $5.24 in new spending on 
Social Security. The report also claims that the taxes to fund the NEA agenda are probably politically 
impractical. According to the report, the NEA would need over thirteen times as much in taxes as was 
raised by the 1993 budget package. Berthoud points out, &quot;no organization that advocates this massive 
expansion of federal spending and probably massive increase in deficits can claim to be helping children. 
This agenda will break the financial back of Americas future generations.&quot; 31 pp.  CONTACT: The Alexis 
de Tocqueville Institution, 1611 North Kent Street, Suite 901, Arlington, VA  22209, 703/351-4969, fax 
703/351-0090.<p>

<B><font size=3>American Higher Education: Behind the Emerald City's Curtain, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Chester Finn and Bruno Manno</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Briefing Paper</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.
188, Hudson Institute</FONT>
<P>
Chester Finn, John M. Olin Fellow at the Hudson Institute, and Bruno Manno, Senior Fellow in the 
Education Policy Studies Program at the Hudson Institute, examine the state of American higher education. 
They point out that although American education has grown in the last fifty years in scale, wealth, allure, 
and stature, it is encountering public disapproval and consumer resistance. Productivity concerns, 
according to Finn and Manno, had been ignored because a college education use to pay off so well in the 
job market. Today, however, that payoff appears to be decreasing while the costs of higher education are 
increasing more quickly than inflation. Furthermore, funding is decreasing, consumers are becoming more 
conscious of costs, and the number of students available for enrollment is less. Finn and Manno claim that 
in order to solve these problems,  higher education must have a greater concern for productivity and a 
willingness to serve customers. They argue that administrators should cut costs, establish tougher entry 
requirements, and concentrate on serious academic subjects. However, they concede, the public will have 
to push them to do so. 16 pp. CONTACT: Hudson Institute, Herman Kahn Center, P.O. Box 26-919, 
Indianapolis, IN  46226, 317/545-1000, 317/545-9639, Internet <a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson">
</a><p>

<B><font size=3>Private Vouchers,  
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> edited by
Terry Moe</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Hoover Institution</FONT></I>
<P>
This book, edited by Terry Moe, Senior Fellow at the Hoover Institution, presents the findings of research 
teams in Indianapolis, Milwaukee, San Antonio, and New York City who have studied four of the largest, 
established private voucher programs in the nation. With detailed analyses of how such programs actually 
operate, these accounts shed new light on a wide range of issues central to the voucher debate, particularly 
on social equity and the effects of vouchers on disadvantaged populations. 135 pp. CONTACT: Hoover 
Institution Press, Stanford University Press, Stanford, CA  94305-6010, 415/723-3373, fax 415/725-8990, 
Internet <a href="http://hoover.standford.edu.">http://hoover.stanford.edu.<p></a>


<B><font size=3> The Great Rhode Island Rip-off: A Commentary, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Myron Lieberman and Charlene Haar</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Social Philosophy & Policy Center</FONT></I>
<P>
This article, published in Government Union Review, examines the little known scandal of teacher union 
bargaining. Myron Lieberman, Senior Research Scholar, and Charlene Haar, Research Associate at the 
Social Philosophy & Policy Center, examine the issue of education union contracts requiring school 
districts to pay for the pensions of union officials. They center on a case in the state of Rhode Island where 
officials of the National Education Association-Rhode Island, and the Rhode Island Federation of Teachers 
benefited from legislation enacted in 1987 which extended the benefits of the states retirement system to 
full-time employees of organizations representing employees of the state and/or any political subdivision 
thereof for the purpose of collective bargaining. Lieberman and Haar also cover the ensuing legal battle 
since the details of the legislation were exposed in the press and subsequently repealed in the Rhode Island 
legislature. They conclude by calling for the prohibition of this practice in other states and encourage 
school boards and state legislatures to adopt safeguards. 14 pp.  CONTACT: Social Philosophy and Policy 
Center, Bowling Green University, Bowling Green, Ohio 43403-1088, 419/372-2536, fax 419/372-8738.
