<font size=5><center><b>Legal Action</b></center></font><p>
<b>CENTER FOR INDIVIDUAL RIGHTS </b>
<p> 
<b>CIR Wins Appeal Challenging Racial Preferences</b><p> CIR won a major victory in March when an unanimous panel of the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals held 
that the university of Texas Law Schools use of racial preferences in student admissions is unconstitutional. CIR represents Cheryl Hopwood and Douglas Carvell, white applicants to the 1992 incoming class of the University of Texas Law School who were denied admission on the basis of their race despite their superior qualifications. In its ruling, the Fifth Circuit declared that diversity is not a 
compelling state interest that would justify the use of racial preferences. The Court stated that [w]ithin the general principles of the fourteenth Amendment, the use of race in admissions for diversity in higher education contradicts, rather than furthers, the aims of equal protection. Diversity fosters, rather than 
minimizes, the use of race. It treats minorities as a group, rather than as individuals. The Fifth Circuit held that Justice Powells opinion in Board of Regents v. Bakke, in which he advocated the consideration of race 
to achieve diversity, never represented the view of a majority of the Supreme Court and, in light of more recent Supreme Court rulings, did not justify the law school race-based admissions program. The Fifth Circuit held further that the government may employ racial preferences only as a means of redressing past 
discrimination by a particular government unitin this case, UT Law School. Racial preferences may not be used to redress alleged discrimination by entire educational systems.  <p>
 
<b>Update on CIR's Case Against HUD Officials</b><p>CIR is representing the Berkeley 3, residents of Berkeley, CA who were targets of a prolonged 
investigation by the Department of Housing and Urban Development.  In response to an administrative complaint filed by a so-called fair housing organization that the residents exercise of their First Amendment rights to protest the governments proposed conversion of a nearby hotel to a homeless shelter constituted discrimination, HUD conducted a lengthy investigation of the residents activities.  CIR filed suit on behalf of the Berkeley 3 against various HUD officers, in both their official and individual capacities, last May.  <p>
 
The Court denied the defendants motion to dismiss on the ground that the complaint failed to state a violation of the First Amendment and that the individual defendants are protected by qualified immunity.  The Court found the defendants arguments that no investigation can violate the First Amendment striking 
in its audacity, and concluded that it would be premature to resolve the issue of qualified immunity solely on the allegations of the complaint.  The Court did grant defendants motion to dismiss plaintiffs injunctive relief claims, but granted plaintiffs leave to replead (which they have done). <p>
 
CONTACT:  Center for Individual Rights,  1300 19th Street, N.W., Suite 260, Washington, DC  20036, 202/833-8400 x104, fax 202/833-8410, E-mail: cir@mail.wdn.com, Internet: http://www.wdn.com/cir/index.html <p>
 
<b>DEFENDERS OF PROPERTY RIGHTS 
</b><p> 
<b>Defenders Tells State It Cannot "Have Its Cake and Eat It Too."</b><p>
Defenders has argued its Motion for Summary Judgment and Opposition to the States Motion to Dismiss 
before Judge Preece of the Ninth Judicial District in Clearwater County, Minnesota.  James Peternell owns 
2/3rd interest in an 112-acre Rice Slough, which the state, pursuant to legislation passed in 1979, classified 
as a public water.  That classification did not, in an of itself, however, change the rights of the property 
owner.  In 1994, the state had criminally prosecuted James Peternell for attempting to exclude from his 
portion of the Rice Slough an uninvited member of the public (who later turned out to be an undercover 
DNR agent) and for leaving duck decoys out overnight on public water.  Although the jury acquitted Mr. 
Peternell of both criminal counts in 1995, Defenders brought its lawsuit alleging that as a result of the 
prosecution, Peternell has lost his right to exclude others from his property in violation of the Fifth 
Amendment.  In response to this lawsuit for compensation, the state has now changed its position.  During 
oral arguments, the state agreed with Defenders that Peternell can exclude members of the public from his 
property.  Defenders is seeking a court order so holding which will force the state to obey the Constitution 
and prevent any further unwarranted criminal prosecutions of Mr. Peternell.   <p>
 
CONTACT:  Defenders of Property Rights, 6235 33rd St., N.W., Washington, DC  20015, 202/686-4197, 
fax 202/686-0240 
<p> 

<b>INSTITUTE FOR JUSTICE </b>
 <p>
<b>Challenge to Davis-Bacon Act</b><p> 
The Institutes opening summary judgment brief in its constitutional challenge to the Davis-Bacon Act was 
filed in the U.S. District Court in Washington, DC.  The lawsuit challenges a 65-year-old federal statute 
controlling wages and job practices on more than one-quarter of all construction contracts in the United 
States, on the grounds of intentional racial discrimination.  The plaintiffs in the case are four minority 
construction contractors, two of which went out of business because of Davis-Bacon, and three public 
housing resident organizations whose members cannot obtain job and training opportunities due to 
prevailing wage requirements. <p>
 
<b>Milwaukee School Choice Oral Arguments</b><p> 
Oral argument before the Wisconsin Supreme Court on the constitutionality of the expanded Milwaukee 
parental choice program was held in Madison, WI.  Nine busloads of parents and children congregated for 
a rally before the argument.  A decision is expected this Spring. 
<p> 
CONTACT: Institute for Justice, 1001 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W., Suite 200 South, Washington., DC  
20004, 202/457-4240, fax 202/457-8574. 
 <p>
<b>MOUNTAIN STATES LEGAL FOUNDATION </B>
<p> 
<b>Sixth Circuit Asks Feds to Respond to MSLF Rehearing Petition</b><p> 
The U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit has ordered the U.S. Forest Service to respond to a petition 
by MSLF fro a rehearing en banc.  MSLFs petition follows the decision by a three judge panel that private 
property in Michigan may be regulated by the Forest Service as a wilderness despite the provision of the 
Wilderness Act of 1964 that only federal land may be classified as wilderness. 
<p> 
Lake front property owners in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan have been told by the U.S. Forest Service 
that their rights to use the entire surface of Crooked Lakea right recognized by Michigan Lawcan be 
denied by the Forest Service since it owns property abutting the southern portion of the Lake. The Forest 
Service claims the Property Clause of the Constitution gives it such authority over private property. 
<p> 
<b>Appeals Court Hears MSLF Challenge to Clinton Tax</b><p> 
A potentially precedent-setting challenge to President Clintons 1993 tax legislation, contending that the 
tax on transportation fuels violates the U.S. Constitution, was heard recently by the U.S. Court of Appeals 
for the Tenth Circuit.  In oral arguments before the three-judge panel, the Wyoming Trucking Association 
asserted that because the transportation fuel tax increase failed to originate in the House of Representatives 
(the House has passed a BTU tax), it violates the Constitutions Origination Clause. 
<p> 
The case is on appeal from federal district court in Wyoming where the Wyoming Trucking Associations 
lawsuit was dismissed when the court held that it had no jurisdiction to hear the case.  The district court 
ruled that any challenge to federal tax liability must first be heard by the Commissioner of the Internal 
Revenue Service.  The Association claims a hearing before the IRS would be futile since it cannot rule 
on challenges to the constitutionality of a tax. 
<p> 
CONTACT:  Mountain States Legal Foundation, 1660 Lincoln Street, Suite 2300, Denver, CO  80264, 
303/861-0244, fax 303/831-7379 
 <p>
<b>NEW ENGLAND LEGAL FOUNDATION </b><p>
 
<b>NELF Brief Aids in Major Win For Massachusetts CPAs.</b><p> 
In a case with national implications, the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court has ruled that the state can 
constitutionally prohibit unlicensed accountants (non-CPAs) from using any language that might mislead 
the public as to their qualifications. The court also held that the state can bar such unlicensed accountants 
from preparing and distributing audits and financial reports to clients or third parties. 
<p> 
The decision involved Mr. Volin, an unlicensed accountant supported by a national association of such 
people.  Volin argued that the First Amendment prohibited the state from preventing non-CPAs from 
claiming the title accountant.  He also claimed the right to use adjectives such as qualified, 
experienced and independent, although he was not licensed by any state or recognized national 
accrediting organization. 
<p> 
But the court agreed with an amicus brief filed by NELF which argued that the states rules promote the 
public interest by protecting clients, financial institutions, suppliers and others from the consequences of 
inaccurate or misleading financial data.  NELFs brief pointed out that every state in the nation has had 
such regulations on the books for decades and that a decision in Volins favor would cause financial 
institutions and suppliers to raise questions about the reliability of financial data regarding the states 
businesses which would harm their ability to engage in interstate and international trade. 
<p> 
The court held that Volin could use the bare word accountant to describe himself, but it barred use of 
modifiers which might imply licensure or special qualifica-tions, and it barred him from distributing 
financial reports.  By upholding the states rules, the court set back national efforts to weaken regulation of 
the accounting profession. 
<p> 
<b>NELF Supreme Court Brief Challenges Expansion of Corporate Liability Under 
Federal Pension Law.</b><p> 
Spink v. Lockheed Corporation involves Lockheeds effort to reduce its defense workforce as a result of 
post-Cold War cutbacks in the defense budget.  One element of Lockheeds effort was to offer workers a 
generous package of additional pension benefits if they agreed to take voluntary early retirement.  Sensibly 
enough, Lockheed coupled that offer with a requirement that workers who accepted enhanced retirement 
benefits must wave possible claims against Lockheed arising from termination of employment.  Lockheed 
added this proviso to protect itself against the increasingly common practice of workers accepting 
enhanced retirement benefits and then suing their former employer claiming violations of the age 
discrimination or other employment-related laws. 
<p> 
Spink refused to sign the waiver and so did not take early retirement. Instead he sued Lockheed, claiming 
that coupling enhanced benefits with a required waiver violated ERISA, the federal pension protection law. 
Spink argued that Lockheed was a fiduciary with respect to assets held under its retirement plan and could 
not use the promise of increased benefits to induce recipients to grant waivers that would protect it. While a 
District Court dismissed Spinks claim, the Court of Appeals in San Francisco reversed. 
<p> 
The case raises two key issues: 1) was the decision to award increased benefits in return for a waiver a 
prohibited transaction in violation of ERISA; and 2) is a corporate plan sponsor an ERISA fiduciary. 
Since Lockheed fully addressed the first issue, NELF only discussed the fiduciary issue. That issue matters, 
because, under ERISA, fiduciaries are subject to civil suits for compensatory damages and attorneys fees, 
while non-fiduciaries are generally subject only to regulatory orders to undo improper actions. 
<p> 
NELFs brief argued that it is irrational to treat plan sponsors as fiduciaries. Corporations are responsible to 
shareholders, not to retirees. While they must obey ERISA and other laws, they cannot put retirees 
interests above their own, as fiduciaries must. The history of ERISA recognizes that plan sponsors and 
fiduciaries, i.e. fund trustees, have different responsibilities. Consistent with pre-existing trust law, under 
ERISA fiduciaries are fully subject to civil suit, while corporations and those that aid them, such as 
accountants and third party benefit administrators, are subject only to regulatory constraints. 
<p> 
<b>NELF Files Amicus Brief in First Circuit Superfund Case.</b><p> 
NELF has filed an amicus brief with the Court of Appeals in a case in which the government seeks to make 
a company pay millions of dollars in Superfund cleanup costs without a chance to defend itself. United 
States v. Cooper Industries involves a Massachusetts site polluted 50 years ago. The Friedlands later 
bought the land and leased it to Cooper Industries. As part of a standard lease, Cooper promised to 
indemnify the Friedlands for costs which they might incur from its activities. Later, after passage of 
CERCLA, the Superfund law, the government sued the Fried lands and Cooper because they owned or 
worked on polluted land. The cleanup estimate was $42 million, with Cooper 22% responsible and the 
Friedlands 29% responsible. 
Then the government hit upon the idea of having the Friedlands use the indemnity provision to pass 
through cleanup costs. Although the clause predated passage of CERCLA, a judge held that it applied to 
CERCLA-related costs. The government then made the Friedlands the proverbial offer they could not 
refuse. If the Friedlands stipulated they were liable for the full $42 million in damages, the government 
would collect the money from indemnity proceeds, i.e., from Cooper. Thus the Friedlands agreed to an 
enormous fine so long as someone else would pay it.  Furthermore, since Cooper had to pay the money 
under the indemnity, not under CERCLA, it could not use any CERCLA defenses or argue that the costs 
were unreasonable or unnecessary. 
<p> 
Obviously, this is grossly unfair to Cooper which must pay millions of dollars in cleanup costs without a 
chance to protect itself. It will also lead to waste in administering CERCLA cleanups. By using the back 
door of indemnity, government can avoid having to prove its costs are reasonable.  Without that check, 
costs will continue to spiral.  A decision on Coopers appeal is likely by summer. 
<p> 
CONTACT: New England Legal Foudnation, 150 Lincoln Street, Boston, MA 02111, 617/695-3660, fax 
617/695-3656. 
<p> 
<b>PACIFIC LEGAL FOUNDATION </b>
<p> 
<b>First Amendment Right to Language Diversity?</b><p> 
As a taxpayer, and ultimately the employer of government workers, do you have the right to set 
reasonable rules concerning the operation of the agencies you underwrite with tax dollars?  Conversely, do 
government workers have a constitutional right to promote their individual agenda by disregarding 
reasonable workplace policies?  More specifically, should state employees be allowed to drag their bosses 
into federal court because they are required to carry out their responsibilities in English?  These 
fundamental questions are at issue in a case in which Pacific Legal Foundation recently asked the U.S. 
Supreme Court to strike down a U.S. Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals ruling Yniguez v. Arizonans for 
Official Language that the free speech right of the public employees are offended by requiring them to 
conduct their jobs in the nations predominant languageEnglish. Should the U.S. Supreme Court accept 
this case, PLF will argue, among other things, that government bureaucrats have no right to turn every 
workplace disagreement into a federal case.  
 <p>
Last October the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals declared unconstitutional Arizonas Official Language 
amendment to the state constitution.  Enacted by Arizona voters in 1988, it declared English the states 
official language and requires the state and all political subdivisions to act in English and in no other 
language.  The amendment applies to all state government employees during the performance of their 
government business.  It is not and outright ban against conversing in a language other than English. 
<p> 
<b>Malibu Declares Moratorium on Constitution</b><p> 
In 1988, Diana Merritt-Shriner and her husband bought 16 acres in Malibu, California, with the intent of 
dividing the lot into three parcels.  They spent three years paying off the loans and formulating their plans 
to build one house on each of the lots.  The county granted tentative parcel approval of the plan in June 
1990, and they subsequently were granted permits buy the Coastal Commission. 
<p> 
All was going well until the creation off the City of Malibu in 1991, when the new city leaders passed a 
law imposing a moratorium on all new development so that it could create and adopt a general plan and 
zoning ordinances.  This turn of events left the Shriners with about $75,000 of incurred expenses and a 16-
acre plot on which no development would be allowed under the terms of the moratorium. 
<p> 
Hard-nosed city bureaucrats denied the Shriners permit request despite state and county rules that would 
have allowed for an exception under unfortunate circumstances.  Although the Shriners land was located 
in a residential neighborhood, the city designated the area as potential open space or parkland even though 
it had no funds with which to purchase the property for those uses!  Furthermore, the county placed a 
Road and Water Assessment Bond against the property in the amount of $279,000 for which the 
Shriners are liable, even though there have not been any water or road impacts since no homes exist on the 
property. 
<p> 
PLF argued to the California Court of Appeal that under circumstances like these, city bureaucrats must not 
abuse their powers in a way that imposes economic hardship on property owners when it is clear that no 
public health, safety, and welfare concerns are being advanced. 
<p> 
CONTACT: Pacific Legal Foundation, 2151 River Plaza Drive, Suite 305, Sacramento CA  95833, 
916/641-8888 
 <p>
<b>WASHINGTON LEGAL FOUNDATION </b>
 <p>
<b>36 Members of Congress Support Florida Suit on Immigration Costs</b><p> 
On behalf of itself and a bipartisan group of five United States Senators (Mack, Graham, DAmato, 
Hutchison, and Feinstein) and 34 Representatives, WLF filed a brief urging the U.S. Supreme Court to hear 
the State of Floridas lawsuit against the federal government in Chiles v. United States.  Florida brought the 
suit to compel the federal government to compensate Florida for the fiscal burdens resulting from the 
federal governments failure to enforce its own immigration laws adequately. 
<p> 
WLFs brief focuses on the fiscal effects of federal mandates upon states to provide education of illegal 
aliens without federal assistance to offset those expenses.  According to WLFs brief, if the federal 
government fails to control illegal immigration adequately, the result is a massive unfunded mandate 
imposed upon the states to provide for the immigrants education and medical care.  Based on the Supreme 
Courts 1992 decision in New York v. United States, WLF argues that although the federal government can 
create incentives for a state to provide such services, it lacks the power to hijack state resources unilaterally 
in this manner. The constitutionality of the federal governments failure to provide reimbursement is not 
just the subject of Floridas suit but of pending litigation brought by other states across the country:  
<p> 
<b>Miranda Decision Superseded by Statute, 
WLF Contends</b><p> 
WLF filed a brief in a Utah bank robbery case, United States v. Nafka, arguing that incriminating 
statements by defendants must be admitted into evidence even if their Miranda right were technically 
violated. WLF pointed out the Miranda has been superseded in federal prosecutions by 18 U.S.C. 3501, 
which provides that statements shall be admissible as evidence if the confession was otherwise voluntary.  
In such cases, according to 3501, the totality of the circumstances should be examined by the trial court.  
Although the U.S. Justice Department has generally failed to invoke 3501 since its enactment in 1968, the 
United States Attorney prosecuting the Utah case has asked the court to consider WLFs arguments. 
<p> 
<b>Apple Growers Ask Supreme Court to 
Hear Appeal</b><p> 
On seventh anniversary of a controversial 60 Minutes broadcast that portrayed apples treated with Alar 
as carcinogenic, a group of Washington State apple growers asked the U.S. Supreme Court to hear their 
suit against CBS for falsity of the broadcast.  The growers, represented by WLF, suffered losses of over 
$75 million from the broadcast, which called Alar  the most potent cancer-causing agent in the food 
supply.  Alar is an EPA-approved growth regulator for apples; according to eminent scientists, there is no 
reliable evidence that Alar causes cancer in humans. In fact, because fruits and vegetables contain 
anticarcinogens, eating them - including those treated with pesticides - is a good way to reduce cancer risk. 
<p> 
CONTACT:  Washington Legal Foundation, 2009 Massachusetts Avenue, N.W., Washington, DC  20036, 
202/588-0302, fax 202/588-0386 
 <p>

<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<a name="of"</a>
<font size=5>Of Note</font><p>
<b>John Locke Foundation Seeks Director for New Center for Education Reform</b><p> 
The Locke Foundation is in the process of forming a special center to focus on issues of higher edcation 
reform. The Pope Center for Higher Education, will study such issues as government financial support for 
higher education, the quality of undergraduate education, tenure and personnel issues, free speech and 
ideological bias on campus, the impact of information and other technologies, and alternative means post-
secondary education and training. Unlike that of the Locke Foundation, the Pope Centers work will be 
national in scope, though an initial focus on higher education in North Carolina is planned. The Locke 
Foundation is looking for someone to serve as director of the Center. Experience in think tanks, public 
policy, development, or journalism is required. Knowledge of, or experience with, issues of higher 
education is preferred. Job responsibilities will include program development, writing and editing, 
fundraising, event planning, and marketing reforms to federal and state policymakers, university 
administrators and faculty, alumni, business executives, student groups, and other audiences. The director 
will also be working with existing national organizations such as the National Association of Scholars and 
the National Alumni Forum. Full benefits and competitive salary will be available. The Pope Center will be 
housed within the Locke Foundations offices in Raliegh, North Carolina. Send cover letter and resume to: 
John Hood, President, The John Locke Foundation, P.O. Box 17822, Raliegh , N.C. 27619, fax 919/847-
8371, e-mail 74157.415@compusereve.com. 
 <p>

<b>Landmark Legal Foundation Seeks New President </b><p>
Landmark Legal Foundation has launched a search to fill the position of president of the organization. 
Landmark is a national, non-profit public interest law firm headquartered in Kansas City, Missouri, with 
offices in Washington, D.C. The organization is involved in policy analysis and litigates in state and 
federal courts throughout the country promoting the issues of limited government, individual rights and a 
free market economy. The individual who serves as president sits on the organizations Board of Directors 
and is responsible to the Board for all aspects of the Foundations operations including administration, 
development, personnel, and legal activity. All Foundation staff report to the president. Applicants should 
possess a clear understanding of major public policy controversies as well as legal and constitutional 
issues. Experience in fundraising, financial management, personel supervision, and media relations is 
required. Applicants must be admitted to practice law and have a thorough understanding of trial and 
appellate practice procedure. Familiarity with the functioning of the legislative and executive branches of 
the federal government also is desirable. Interested applicants should send a cover letter and resume to: 
Jerald L. Hill, President, Landmark Legal Foundation, Suite 2310, 2345 Grand Avenue, Kansas City, 
Missouri 64108. 
 <p>
<b>Institute for American Values Seeks Director of Finance and Administration </b>
<p>
The Institute for American Values, located in New York City, is a private, nonpartisan organization 
devoted to research, publication, and public education on major issues of family well-being, family policy, 
and civil society. Their mission is to examine the status of the family as a social institution and to explore 
the social sources of competence, character, and citizenship in the United States. The Director of Finance 
and Administration oversees the current annual budget of $500,000. The Director is responsible for all 
aspects of financial management, accounting, coordination of annual audit, and finance and program 
reporting to financial contributors, and assists the President with fundraising and proposal writing. As 
senior administrative officer, the Director plans and carries out logistics for scholarly conferences, research 
and book projects, Board meetings, and other Institute activities and supervises the office manager. Salary 
$40-45,000, negotiable, good benefits. CONTACT: David Brenner, Institute for American Values, 1841 
Broadway, Suite 211, New York, NY 10023, 212/246-3942, fax 212/541-6665.  
<p> 
<b>The 18th Annual Publius Fellows Program </b><p>
The Publius Fellows Program is an intensive four-week summer course in political philosophy designed for 
college seniors and graduate students who are interested in writing for the public prints. Now in its 
eighteenth year, the Publius Fellows Program is dedicated to preserving the tradition of American political 
writing. It aims to foster constructive commentary on the important issues of today, informed and 
moderated by an understanding of the philosophical and historical roots of American democracy. 
CONTACT: Publius Fellows Program, The Claremont Institute, 250 West First Street, Suite 330, 
Claremont, CA 91711, 909/621-6825, fax 909/626-8724. 
 <p>
<b>Claremont Institute Sponsors Abraham Lincoln Fellowships in Constitutional Government </b><p>
The Claremont Institute announces the establishment of the Abraham Lincoln Fellowships in 
Constitutional Government. Participation is open to young professionals serving elected officials or 
appointed policy-makers in the U.S. Congress and the executive branch of the federal government, as well 
as staff members in national political parties and non-profit institutions dedicated to constitutional issues. 
Up to ten Abraham Lincoln Fellowships will be awarded annually. Fellows will be selected each spring 
from among the applications recommended by a panel of distinguished elected officials and scholars. 
Applications are available from The Claremont Institute. Each Lincoln Fellow will serve a one year term, 
commencing in August with a one-week seminar in constitutional theory and practice led by eminent 
scholars. Lincoln Fellows receive a stipend of $1500 and all expenses related to seminars and other 
programs. CONTACT: The Claremont Institute, 250 West First Street, Suite 330, Claremont, CA 91711, 
909/621-6825, fax 909/626-8724. 
