<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/lead-inst/pac/pacstudy.html 204.71.237.74 19970108144131 text/html 37980
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 14:41:45 GMT
Last-modified: Wednesday, 07-Aug-96 17:06:50 GMT
Content-length: 37790
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Business & Association PAC Study
</title></head>
<body>
<center>
<img src="/lead-inst/nw-logo.gif" align="left"><h2>1993-94 ELECTION CYCLE<br>
BUSINESS<br>
&<br>
ASSOCIATION<br>
PAC STUDY</h2>
<hr><h3>
BY<br>
FRANCIS A. SCHAEFFER VI<br>
TERRANCE J. McINTYRE<br>
<p>
TECHNICAL ASSISTANT<br>
MICHAEL C. HIGGS<br>
<p>
WITH AN INTRODUCTION BY<br>
MORTON C. BLACKWELL
<p></h3>
</center>
<font size="-1">
The Leadership Institute is a non-partisan educational organization determined by the Internal Revenue Service to be a public foundation operating under Sec. 501 (c) (3) of the Internal Revenue Code. The Institute does not support or oppose candidates or proposed legislation.
<br>
Opinions expressed in this study are not necessarily those of the Leadership Institute.
<br>
Contributions to the Leadership Institute by individuals, corporations and foundations are tax deductible.
<br>
Copyright (C) 1995
</font>
<p>
<hr>
<center><b>
 Introduction</b></center>
<p>
In 1996 the Congress may vote on a "campaign finance reform" bill designed to eliminate political action committees (PACs) from the American political system. On this issue, liberals have found peculiar allies. Some Americans who generally favor maximizing economic and political freedoms say political action committees (PACs) are irredeemably evil and should be abolished.
<p>
President George Bush repeatedly said he wanted to abolish PACs. As described below, he subsequently narrowed his focus to the abolition of a certain type of PAC, the "<i>connected</i>" PAC. But the hue and cry against PACs-has risen anew. Senator John McCain, Congresswoman Linda Smith and presidential candidate Pat Buchanan have joined the liberal media establishment's drumbeat against all PACs.
<p>
Very few Americans have a good understanding of what PACs are or what they really do.
<p>
Public disclosure of PAC financial activity has not helped public understanding very much.
<p>
Yes, financial data on the activities of all PACs at the federal level is available at the Federal Election Commission (FEC). And some helpful FEC staff do their best to assist researchers. But the mass of data is too great for easy comprehension.
<p>
PAC financial data the public sees most often are bits and pieces selected by reporters and activists looking for scandal or attempting to discredit opponents.
<p>
No wonder PACs rate down there with used car salesmen in mistrust by the public.
<p>
<b><center>
The Attack on PACs
</b></center><p>
It was not always so. Before the early 1970s, labor unions had a virtual monopoly of PACs. And very effective PACs they were. But there was little agitation against PACs in those days.
<p>
Upon the rise in the 1970s of corporate and association PACs and, to a lesser extent, of conservative PACs, liberals in the news media and elsewhere in the public policy process began to complain bitterly about PACs. Only when the Left's near monopoly of PACs was broken did liberals begin to see PACs as a public nuisance.
<p>
Today most liberal activists would be delighted to abolish all PACs.
<p>
This <i>would</i> mean the end of labor union PACs, all of them liberal. But eliminating all PACs would work to the net benefit of organized labor.
<p>
PAC abolition would destroy the organized campaign participation of business interests and conservative groups while leaving untouched the vast majority of political expenditures by labor unions. Most union political spending is not through PACs but in categories not significant for business interests. The unions bosses' greatest political clout comes, not from their PACs, but from two types of political effort not reported to the Federal Election Commission:

<ul><li> huge "in-kind" expenditures of (largely compulsory) union dues money in election-related activities such as selective voter registration, campaign mailings and get out the vote activities

<li> massive deployment of paid union staff in the campaigns of their chosen candidates.
</ul>
Neither of these forms of support would be adversely affected by the complete abolition of PACs, which would leave organized labor, including the teachers unions, the only major players in politics outside of the political party organizations and the news media.
<p>
<b><center>
What PACs Really Do
</b></center><p>
For many years there was a general belief that labor unions supported liberal and Democratic candidates and that business and association PACs supported conservative and Republican candidates.
<p>
Conventional wisdom was right about labor union political contributions but not about business and association political giving.
<p>
According to the Federal Election Commission records, the 254 active labor union PACs gave $41,867,393 to Federal candidates in the last election cycle, 1993-94. Of this sum, 95.4% went to Democrats and 4.2% to Republicans.
<p>
This Leadership Institute study found that in 1993-94 the 864 largest corporate business PACs and trade association and professional PACs gave a total of $ 118,709,400 in contributions to Federal candidates, 51.6% of it to Democrats.
<p>
These largest 864 business PACs accounted for close to 90% of the donations of all business-related PACs.
<p>
The FEC assigns a separate category to labor union PACs, but it doesn't compile exact, aggregate numbers for PACs tied to businesses or to professional or trade associations. Business related PACs are mixed by the FEC in categories which also include many ideological, ethnic and cause-oriented PACs. It's no easy job to sort them out, as has been done in this study by looking individually at all non-labor union PACs which gave contributions totaling $25,000 or more in the 1993-94 period.
<p>
I have followed trends in the political action community for a long time. In 1972 I founded one of the earliest independent conservative PACs, which is still in operation. In the 1970s I published studies of the donations of business and association PACs in the election cycles of 1975-76 and 1977-78. In late 1980 and early 1981, I served on the Transition Team for the Federal Election Commission
 for President-elect Ronald Reagan. In 1989 I published a study of giving patterns of the 775 then-largest business and association PACs in the 1987-88 election cycle.
<p>
The corporate, professional and trade association PACs vary individually in their behavior much more than do the labor union PACs. Many business- related PACs are consistent donors to liberal and Democratic candidates.
<p>
From the mass of data filed at the FEC, this study extracts key facts about all the major business PACs in the 1993-94 election cycle and puts information before the public about each PAC studied in context with the activities of the other major such PACs.
<p><b>
<center>
PAC Behavior Changes
</center></b><p>
Here's a quick summary of business PAC developments in the past twenty years or so.
<p>
The Federal Election Commission was formed in 1974 to supplant the previous system of campaign finance disclosure, which had required reporting of campaign finance activity to the Clerk of the House of Representatives, the Secretary of the Senate and the General Accounting Office.
<p>
Business PACs began in earnest after the famous 1975 SUNPAC advisory opinion in which the then-new Federal Election Commission determined that businesses could organize PACs just as labor unions had done for many years.
<p>
In the middle 1970s the new business PACs shocked conservatives and Republicans by giving a lot of money to liberals and Democrats. Public exposure of these giving patterns caused many of the business-related PACs to change their ways.
<p>
By 1978 and 1980, most business PACs were squarely in the conservative Republican camp.
<p>
And no doubt the increasingly conservative congressional election results in those years were caused in part by the business PAC donations.
<p>
But in 1981 -82, then-Congressman Tony Coelho, chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, embarked on an extremely aggressive approach to raise money for Democrats from the business community.
<p>
Pointing out that Democrats controlled the House of Representatives, he warned the business PAC community in private meetings that strongly anti-business legislation would be passed if the business PACs didn't give more money to Democrats. He went beyond general threats and pointed out to business leaders specific kinds of hostile legislation which might be passed to hurt them.
<p>
Most political observers at the national level agree that Representative Coelho's pressure tactics worked.
<p>
By the 1988 elections, many business-related PACs were giving much more to Democrats than in the past. Republicans lost their former edge in business PAC donations. In recent election cycles, business PAC growth slowed, and Democrats got half or more of business PAC contributions.
<p>
Nevertheless, the drumbeat against PACs in the news media is now almost deafening, perhaps because of reports that business PAC contributions to Republicans have increased since the GOP won majorities in the U.S. House and Senate in 1994.
<p>
Liberal activist groups attacking PACs receive enthusiastic coverage by reporters and commentators. Over the years, some business organizations reacted to the general criticism of PACs by reducing their political activity.
<p>
Many conservative movement PACs have found it harder to raise funds in recent election cycles. Some have disappeared.
<p>
With these trends in mind, the time has come for another serious, systematic look at the reality of political action committees associated with the business community: business corporation PACs and PACs associated with professional organizations, trade associations or other business interests.
<p>
<b><center>
Just What is a PAC?
</center></b><p>
At the Federal level, a political action committee is an organization which receives voluntary contributions and makes expenditures intended to influence the outcome of elections to either branch of the United States Congress or the presidency and vice-presidency. 
<p>
Corporations and labor unions may not contribute to PACs. But business corporations, professional groups, trade associations, labor unions and other existing organizations may, under current law, organize and pay all operating expenses of their own PACs. Such organizations are called "connected" PACs. Here are the major differences between connected and non-connected PACs:
<ul>
<li> Non-connected PACs must pay all the costs of their operations from voluntary contributions from U.S. citizens. They may solicit contributions from any American.

<li>Connected PACs may have their operating expenses (staff salaries, lawyers' fees, fundraising costs, etc.) paid by their parent organizations. They may solicit contributions only from people affiliated as members or employees of their sponsoring organizations. They may not legally give or spend corporate or union resources for a candidate for Federal office.
</ul>
By law, all contributions by a PAC to candidates for Federal office must be drawn entirely from voluntary donations to the PAC from individual United States citizens.
<p>
Two attributes are common to all PACs, whether corporate, professional association, labor union, independent, ideological, connected, non-connected or whatever:
<ul>
<li> All donors to each PAC are American citizens voluntarily participating together in the democratic process.

<li>There is full public disclosure of names, employers, addresses and amounts given of all donors of who cumulatively give more than $200 to any PAC, as well as how each PAC spends and donates its money.
</ul>
In Federal elections, the law limits individual and PAC contributions:
<ul>
<li> Individuals may give a candidate up to $1,000 per election. A primary counts as a separate election.

<li> Individuals may give up to $5,000 per year to a single PAC and up to a grand total of $25,000 per year to all Federal candidates and PACs.

<li> PACs may give a candidate up to $5,000 per election.
</ul>
Desirable or not, these are significant limits on citizens' rights to voluntary political participation. These financial limits are not indexed for inflation. And they are probably very close to the outer limit of restrictions the Supreme Court would allow.
<p>
In the 1976 <i>Buckley v. Valeo</i> decision, the Court struck down some serious, further restrictions pushed through Congress in the first wave of legislative attacks on citizen participation through PACs.
<p>
<center>
<b>Why PACs are Formed</b>
</center><p>
Public opinion pollsters work hard to discover the different preferences of voters. Voters' motives may be guessed at, but the secret ballot is a legal right. Even the best-paid pollsters are sometimes embarrassingly wrong.
<p>
Similarly, the motivations of citizens who organize and give to PACs are varied and hard to analyze.
<p>
Many who would abolish PACs make a seldom-spoken presumption that all who participate in PACs are ill-motivated. But given the occasion to reflect, even anti-PAC zealots would probably concede that most people participate in PACs for about the same range of reasons which motivate them to vote.
<p>
Prominent among the many reasons why people vote and give to PACs are:
<ul>
<li>political philosophy
<li>self-identification with one kind of candidate

<li> dislike of another kind of candidate

 <li> perceived self-interest

<li> the recommendation of a trusted friend
</ul>
Do motives which are acceptable if held individually by voters become unacceptable if held by groups of voters voluntarily participating together in politics? That would be a tricky case to argue from a constitutional perspective.
<p>
But those who would abolish or cripple PACs simply avoid discussing in this context the subjects of freedom of speech and freedom of association.
<p>
Should Americans have the freedom to try to persuade others in the political process? That is the key question. But anti-PAC activists use the full arsenal of demagogy. Their arguments rely mainly on pejoratives, name calling. And many of these activists are long-time liberals who kept silent about PACs until conservative and business-oriented PACs arose.
<p>
To what extent is anti-PAC activism motivated by a desire to run conservatives and the business community out of politics?
<p>
One might deny people in the business and professional community the right to organize themselves voluntarily in politics because one does not like what they do in election campaigns.
<p>
But that could be compared to the former practice of denying blacks the franchise because many did not like the way they would vote.
<p>
<b><center>
The Current Threat to Citizen Participation
</b></center><p>
Any plan to abolish PACs necessarily involves prohibiting Americans from voluntarily associating with others to support candidates and causes of their choice.
<p>
Recently, much of the world threw off 1 system which denied citizens the right to participate voluntarily in political activity. It is ironic that "the land of the free" is seriously contemplating further restrictions on citizens' political rights.
<p>
I was present during discussions President Bush had, soon after his election, with conservative leaders on the topic of "campaign finance reform." President Bush quite clearly described what "reform" legislation he would sign.
<p>
He described a package of legislative changes which he promised the conservative leaders would be passed as a package or not at all.
<p>
Most gratifying to those present was his pledge to veto any bill to abolish the "ideological" PACs, a matter certainly important to those in that meeting. The White House announcement of the President's proposal June 29, 1989, stated, "It appears that freedom of association guarantees under the First Amendment make it impossible to eliminate these independent PACs."
<p>
Thus President Bush would have preserved citizens' rights to join together to support causes and candidates important to them.
<p>
So, for example, citizens opposing legalized abortion, as well as citizens advocating it, would retain their freedom to form and fund political action committees.
<p>
Having given this firm pledge to important members of the political coalition who elected him, President Bush guaranteed, for his time in office, the survival of ideological PACs.
<p>
His "reform" package did include, however, the abolition of most of the corporate, association and labor union PACs, at least in the form they now exist.
<p>
To do this, President Bush proposed simply to outlaw the <i>connected</i> PACs, which the White House estimated as having given "nearly 90% of the approximately $160 million contributed in the 1987-88 election cycle."
<p>
In the words of the June 29, 1989 White House statement, the effect of enacting this one of the President's proposed reforms would have been:
<br><blockquote>
Eliminating political action committees (PACs) supported by
corporations, unions or trade associations, and prohibiting such entities
from paying for the overhead or administrative cost of any independent
PAC.
</blockquote>
<p>
"Connected" corporate and union PACs and most trade and professional association PACs have their operating expenses paid by their parent organizations. Abolishing connected PACs would force most of these PACs to shut down. Many of these PACs simply couldn't afford to pay their own operating costs.
<p>
After such a change in the law, the surviving PACs of labor union interests and business-related interests would have to pay all PAC operating costs out of voluntary citizen donations, as nearly all ideological, conservative movement and liberal activist PACs do now.
<p>
Some conservatives find charm in the idea of the government shutting down the business-related PACs. After all, many of these PACs support mostly liberals and all but a handful support some liberals. But conservatives of this mind may be making the perfect the enemy of the good, increasing the political power of the generally liberal news media and paving the way for greater bureaucratic control of the political process.
<p>
As limited government advocate Barry Goldwater pointed out many years ago, "A government big enough to give you everything you want is big enough to take everything you've got."
<p>
Linked to the principle of limited government is the prudential question of whether or not to allow the political participation of the economically productive sectors of our society. Two hundred years ago, British statesman and political philosopher Edmund Burke warned against destroying participation of any major element in the public policy process. Burke wrote:
<p><blockquote>
The opposed and conflicting interests, which you considered as so great a blemish in our old and in our present Constitution, interpose a salutary check to all precipitate resolutions. They render deliberation, not a matter of choice, but of necessity; they make all change a matter of <i>compromise</i>, which naturally begets moderation; they produce <i>temperaments</i>, preventing the sore evil of harsh, crude, unqualified reformations, and rendering all the headlong exertions of arbitrary power, in the few or in the many, forever impracticable.
</blockquote>
<p><b><center>
PACs Will Survive, at Least for Now
</b></center><p>
The vast majority of organized labor's great political power is due to currently unreported, in-kind contributions and expenditures, including selective voter registration drives, targeted voter turnout programs and the salaries of uncounted thousands of union staffers poured each year into election campaigns.
<p>
Union payrolls total approximately $10 million per day.
<p>
Democrats in Congress would never vote to curtail the political uses of compulsory union dues. A reform of this nature would surely be vetoed by President Bill Clinton. The current Republican majorities in Congress would never vote to eliminate PACs without curbing the other ways in which unions alone impact on election campaigns. So an outright abolition of PACs is unlikely to become law any time soon. And a law simply abolishing all PACs would almost certainly be declared by the Supreme Court to be an unconstitutional restriction of political freedom.
<p>
From the government, therefore, nothing more than tinkering with current campaign finance law is likely now.
<p><b><center>
Knowledge about PACs is Useful
</center></b><p>
Although business and association PACs seem certain to survive any current attempt to destroy them, abundant experience proves they are far more easily influenced than are any other types of PACs.
<p>
Labor union bosses have such tight control over their organizations that few of their decisions, about their PACs or anything else, are ever effectively challenged from within. Ideological PACs, right or left, usually have very predictable, clear and unshakable ideas of what is in their interest.
<p>
But business corporations and professional and trade associations are, shall we say, more flexible in their PAC decisions. They are responsive to any of the following possible influences on them: 
<blockquote><p>
stockholders, employees, customers, boards of directors, clients, members, partners, colleagues, politicians, news media and the general public.
</blockquote>
Often those who make decisions in business and association PACs are the Washington lobbyists have who have risen in life by trying to make almost everybody happy.
<p>
They tend to be non-confrontational. They love to be loved and fear to be hated.
<p>
As this study amply demonstrates, their PACs tend to contribute to incumbents rather than to challengers or candidates for open seats. Most are more interested in influencing incumbents, or at least in having access to incumbents, than they are in influencing the outcome of elections.
<p>
Prudent or not, the business and association PACs have every right to act as they do, as all the money they dispense is voluntarily given to them.
<p>
But their very nature makes them responsive to many sources of influence on their behavior.
<p>
One purpose of the FEC's legally-required public disclosure of PAC financial data is undoubtedly to give citizens knowledge they can use to influence a PACs future decisions.
<p>
Without advocating any course of action, this study makes public the giving patterns of the largest business and association PACs, 864 PACs which each contributed a total of $25,000 or more in the last election cycle, 1993-94.
<p>
Armed with this information, stockholders, employees, customers, boards of directors, clients, members, partners, colleagues, politicians, news media and the general public will be better able to decide for themselves what actions, if any, they should take regarding business and association PACs in which they are interested.
<p>
In 1979, after publication of my PAC study of the 1977-78 election cycle, I was visited by two, three-piece suited officials of the National Forest Products Association. They came to my office to explain why a forest industry PAC just <i>had</i> to give to the re-election campaign of a famous, very liberal congressman from Illinois.
<p>
Those forestry industry officials were sweating because conservative members of their association had chewed them out. In subsequent election cycles they, and others, changed their behavior significantly.
<p>
In another case that same year, a major stockholder of a big supermarket chain got so hot she nearly peeled the paint off the wall at the corporate headquarters because she didn't like what she learned about their PACs giving pattern. They too changed their behavior.
<p>
<b><center>
PACs in Context
</center></b><p>
The records of political fundraising and expenditures at the Federal Election Commission are open to the public. Staffers there do their best to help inquirers. But even their computerized data base of financial data is not 100% reliable.
<p>
An avalanche of regular financial reports pour into the FEC from candidates, PACs and party committees.
<p>
These detailed reports sometimes contain accidental errors from the thousands of organizations required to file reports. Computer data entry of these reports by the FEC is another source of error. For example, a $ 10.00 donation may, by a data entry error, appear on the FEC computer record as a $ 1000 donation.
<p>
I mention the inevitable, if rare, errors to caution readers of this report. The extraordinary bright, dedicated and careful researchers, Francis Schaeffer and Terry McIntyre, who prepared and rechecked the tabulations in the body of this study were entirely dependent on information from the FEC, which is known to be imperfect.
<p>
Nonetheless, the FEC data, usually reliable, is the best available.
<p>
Here are some aggregate totals for political activity at the Federal level in the 1993-94 election cycle, according to the FEC reports:
<ul>
<li>There were 2,414 candidates for U.S. Senate and U.S. House of Representatives .

<li>They received from all sources a total of $740,474,131, up from $477,608,990 for all congressional candidates in the 1987-88 election cycle. Republican candidates received from all sources $385,332,893, up from $267,959,244 in 1987-88. Democratic candidates received 350,291,422, up from $267,959,244 in 198788. Independents and others received $4,849,816, up from $1,318,782 in 1987-88.

<li>A total of 437 Republican and Democratic party committees reported financial activity to the FEC.

<li>These party committees received an aggregate of $440,837,137. Republican Party committees received $266,472,079, or 60.4% of the total.

<li>There were a total of 2,978 Federal PACs of all kinds active in the 199394 cycle, down from 3,308 in 1987-88. They received a total of $391,760,117, little changed from $384,617,093 in 1987-88.

<li> They contributed, to all candidates for the U.S. House and Senate, a total of $189,631,119, compared to $147,846,057 in 1987-88.

<li>To Republican candidates, PACs gave $71,633,571, or 38%, compared to $56,267,883 and 38% in 1978-88. To Democratic candidates, PACs gave $117,683,963, 62%.

<li>Individuals personally gave U.S. House and Senate candidates a total of $402,534,070, up from $232,605,508 in 1987-88.

<li> Republicans received $219,470,179, or 54% from individuals, up from $115,853,176 and 50% in 1978-88. Democrats received $180,678,908, or
45%, up from $115,870,844 in 1987-88.

<li> There were 254 labor union PACs active in 1993-94, down from 256 in 1987-88. Not counting the unreported, election related expenditures of
union dues money, the labor union PACs contributed, to congressional
candidates for both houses of Congress, a total of $42,867,393, up from
$32,460,094 in 1987-88.

<li> To Republican candidates, union PACs gave $1,763,842, or 4%,
compared to $2,477,718, or 8%, in 1987-88. To Democrats, labor union
PACs gave $39,947,651, or 95%, compared to $29,982,676, or 92%, in
1987-88.
</ul>
As mentioned above, PACs related to business corporations and professional and trade associations are mixed together with ideological, ethnic and other PACs in the FEC's system of categories. So any analysis of the business-related PACs must involve picking, one by one, those PACs really linked to business, trade and professional interests.
<p>
To keep this study manageable, we focus here on the 864 largest (contributions totaling $25,000 or more) of the "economic interest" PACs, which include the business corporation PACs and the professional and trade organization PACs. Also included were the large ($25,000 or more) PACs which we judged to have primarily economic or professional reasons for being.
<p>
In some cases, inclusion was a close decision. PACs of law firms were included. PACs organized by gun owners to support the right to keep and bear arms were not included as they are primarily non-economic in their purpose.
<p>
But the PACs of both the Boat Owners Association and the Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association, in a close decision, were included because their interests were deemed largely based on their economic interest. 
<p>
All 864 PACs were those we found to be business-related and which gave or expended $25,000 or more in the 1993-94 election cycle.
<blockquote>
In sum, these 864 largest business and association PACs gave $ 118,709,400 to Federal candidates, up from $97,084,426 from business PACs which gave $25,000 or more in 1987-88. They gave $61,204,865 or 52%, to Democrats, up from $47,846,163, or 49.3%, in 1987-88 and $57,529,107, or 48%, to Republicans, compared to $49,243,263, or 50.7%, in 1987-88.
</blockquote>
The business and association PACs studied here accounted for the great majority, close to 90%, of business and association PAC giving in the 1993-94 election cycle.
<p>
The 864 PACs studied ranged in size from the United Parcel Service PAC, based in Atlanta, Georgia, total given $2,646,113, to the Advertising Mail Marketing Association PAC, based in Washington, D.C., total given, exactly $25,000.
<p>
The average given by the 864 PACs was $137,395, up from $125,270 for the average business PAC giving $25,000 or more in 1987-88. The median in size among the 864 studied PACs in 1993-94 was the Union Camp Corporation PAC, of Wayne, New Jersey, which gave $66,175.

<p><b><center>
Content of this Study
</center></b><p>
The main body of this study lists, in alphabetical order, the 864 business-association PACs which gave or spent $25,000 or more in 1993-94.
<p><i>
Name, Address, Size and Rank by Size
</i><p>
Included is each PACs mailing address as filed with the Federal Election Commission.
<p>
The amount each PAC gave in 1993-94 and its rank in size, by dollar amount, among the 864 PACs are also given.
<p>
Take, for example, Abbott Laboratories Better Government Fund. This PAC is listed on page 1.
<p>
Abbott's PAC gave candidates $145,169 in 1993-94. This PAC ranked 211th in size among the business PACs.
<p>
<i>Giving to Republicans and Democrats
</i><p>
The next two columns list the respective percentages of each PACs donations to Republican candidates and its rank among the 864 PACs in the percentage of its contributions which went to Republicans.
<p>
Note that Abbott gave 54.3% to Republicans and ranked 329 in the percentage of its total contributions which went to Republicans. (The asterisk (*) indicates Abbott tied with one or more other PACs in this ranking for partisan giving.
<p>
Next is listed the percentage of donations going to Democratic candidates and its rank among the 864 PACs in the percentage of its money going to Democratic candidates.
<p>
Abbott gave 45.5% of its total contributions to Democrats and ranked 535th highest in percentage of its giving to Democrats.
<p><i>
Giving to Incumbents and to Non-Incumbents
</i><p>
In the next column is listed the percentage of each PACs money which went to incumbents. The balance went to challenger candidates or candidates for open seats.
<p>
Abbott gave 77.5% of its funds to incumbents.
<p>
Next is the rank of each PAC as measured by the percentage of its money which went to incumbents. Abbott ranked 512th highest in giving money to incumbents.
<p>
Number one in rank in the category of giving to incumbents was an eleven way tie. Eleven of the 864 PACs gave 100% to incumbents.
<p>
The lowest in percentage given to incumbents (and therefore the highest percentage given to challengers and candidates for open seats) was Precision Metalforming Association PAC, which gave only 3.1 % of its donations to incumbents.
<p>
By and large, the business and association PACs gave <i>overwhelmingly</i> to incumbents.
<p><i>
Giving to Conservatives and Liberals
</i><p>
The final four columns in the main part of this study relate to each PACs giving in the principal liberal versus conservative contests of 1993-94.
<p>
To measure each of the 864 biggest business and association PACs giving to conservative candidates and to liberal candidates, it was necessary first to devise a method of determining which candidates could be properly be described as conservatives and which could be described as liberals.
<p>
The best available way to determine which candidates were conservative was to identify the candidates who received contributions from a variety of known, philosophically conservative PACs.
<p>
The following method was used:
<ol>
<li> A dozen different politically knowledgeable conservatives were each asked to list all those PACs which they believed to be the most representative of the conservative cause, broadly considered.
<p>
We asked them to name PACs they believed most notable for their commitment to any or all of the following generally-understood conservative principles:
<ul>
<li>Limited government
<li>Free enterprise
<li>Strong national defense
<li>Traditional Family Values
</ul>
The resulting list of 21 conservative PACs included representation from the major elements of the conservative winning coalition in the presidential races of 1980, 1984 and 1988 and the congressional races of 1994. The PACs included were:
<p><ul>
<li>ACU-PAC
<li>America's PAC
<li>Business and Industry PAC
<p>
<li>Citizens for the Republic
<li>Conservative Campaign Fund
<li>Conservative Leadership PAC
<p>
<li>Conservative Victory Committee
<li>Conservative Victory Fund
<li>Eagle Forum PAC
<p>
<li>Free Congress PAC
<li>Funds for A Conservative Majority
<li>Gun Owners of America Political Victory Fund
<p>
<li>Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association
<li>Justice PAC
<li>Mid-America Conservative PAC
<p>
<li>National Federation of Independent Business PAC
<li>National Rifle Association Political Victory Fund
<li>National Right to Life PAC
<p>
<li>Public Service PAC
<li>Right to Work PAC
<li>Ruff PAC
</uL>
<li> From FEC records, the list of all candidates supported by each conservative PAC was obtained.

<li> Any candidate supported by any three of these 21 conservative PACs was <i>defined</i> as a conservative candidate for the purpose of this study. There were 198 conservative candidates selected by this process.

<li> Any candidate who ran against one of the defined conservative candidates was defined, for the special purpose of this study, as a liberal (non-conservative). (Except in the very few cases where, in a primary, two candidates defined as conservatives were opposing each other.)
<br>
There were 1,110 opponents to conservative candidates identified in this way. It might seem that 1,110 is a large number, but it included all other candidates (primary, general election, minor party and independent) running in races for seats sought by the specified conservative candidates. Very few of the 1,110 who were not major party candidates, received any business PAC contributions.

<li> The next step was the most difficult. Each contribution of each of the 864 PACs was examined to see if it went to a candidate on either the conservative list or the liberal list. The financial support each PAC gave to all the conservative candidates was totaled, as was each PACs support of the liberal candidates.

<li> Then each PACs combined amount given to all candidates in these selected, liberal versus conservative races was totaled.

<li> Each PACs total giving to all candidates in the selected liberal versus conservative races was then calculated as a percentage of its total giving.
<br>
Look again on page 1. Abbott gave 61.3% of all its donations to candidates in the selected, liberal versus conservative races.

<li> Then each PACs percentage of giving respectively to liberals and to conservatives within the selected races was calculated.
<br>
Of its 61.3% Abbott gave in the liberal versus conservative races, 61.0% went to conservatives and 39.0% to liberals.

<li> Finally we calculated each PACs rank among the 864 PACs as measured by its percentage of giving to liberal candidates in the selected races.
<br>
Abbott ranked 528th highest in giving to liberals in the selected races.
</ol>
Four of the business and association PACs gave 100% of their contributions in the selected races to liberals. Seven of these 864 PACs gave conservatives 100% of their contributions in the selected races. Measured by the ranking of what the 864 PACs gave in the liberal versus conservative races, the median business and association PACs gave 45% to liberal candidates.
<p>
In aggregate, the business PACs were no bastions of conservatism.
<p><br>
<b><center>
 Six Top Fifty Lists
</b></center><p>
Starting on page 49, ranked by percentage of donations given in different categories, are six lists of the TOP FIFTY business and association PACs. The categories are:
<ul>
<a name="list">
<li><a href="repub.html">PAC Donors to Republicans</a> 
<p>
<li><a href="demo.html">PAC Donors to Democrats</a> 
<p>
<li><a href="inc.html">PAC Donors to Incumbents</a> 
<p>
<li><a href="nonin.html">PAC Donors to Non-Incumbents</a> 
<p>
<li><a href="cons.html">PAC Donors to Conservatives</a> 
<p>
<li><a href="lib.html">PAC Donors to Liberals</a>
</ul>
<p><b><center>
Using this PAC Study
</b></center><p>
Federal law prohibits use of information obtained about individual contributors from the Federal Election Commission for fundraising or "any commercial purpose." But an FEC publication points out, "This restriction applies only to the use of individual contributor information, not to the use of names and addresses of political committees." 
<p>
Data from the FEC regarding PACs may be used freely by anyone, including news reporters, scholars and the general public. Among the obvious uses are: to publicize, to study, to praise or to condemn.
<center>
Morton C. Blackwell<br>
February, 1996
</center>
<p><br>
