<title>
<head>
<title>Trained Conservatives Bridge Leadership Gap</title>
</head>

<body>

<center>
<h2>Trained Conservatives Bridge Leadership Gap</h2>
</center> 

William R. Jackson, Sr. is <i>an arch-conservative</i>.<p>

To a liberal in the establishment media, longtime Leadership Institute supporter Bill Jackson might be called an archconservative simply because he supports limited government , free enterprise and traditional values.  But if that's the case he's an arch conservative in more ways than one.<p>

Because of Bill Jackson and his company, Pitt-Des Moines, millions of Americans every year enjoy a visit to America's "Gateway to the West" -- the Arch at St. Louis.

<center>
<h4>Bridge Builder Demonstrates Sucess of American Free Enterprise System</h4>
</center>

In 1982, Bill Jackson's father, William H. Jackson, founded Jackson and Moss with his partner and friend, Berkely Moss, to install water systems for small towns.  At the time, wood was the primary resource for building water tanks.<p>  

Their company grew into Des Moines Bridge and Iron Works, with its headquarters in Des Moines, Iowa.  With the increasee use and production of steel, it evolved into Pittsburgh-Des Moines Steel Company.  Now it has operations inWarren, Pennsyulvania; Des Moines, Iowa; Provo, Utah; and several cities in California.  <p>

Today, Pitt-Des Moines still builds water towers -- and bridges, wind tunnels, space chambers and storage tanks for natural gas and oil.<p>

But, the best known product of Pitt-Des Miones is something quite different -- America's "Gateway to the West" -- The Arch at St. Louis.<p>

<h4>Jackson's Company Built Perfect Symbol of Growth</h4>

In 1962, Pitt-Des Moines was chosen to construct the "Gateway to the West" to commemorate the pioneers' great western movement.  <p>

Bill Jackson explains his revolutionary Catenary arch as equally wide as it is tall at 630 feet each.  The Arch is shaped at the base and all around as an equilateral triangle.  At the base, each side of the triangle is 54 feet long. <p>
 
The Arch was assembed by welding eight-foot-tall stainless steel pieces into triangle-shaped sections, buildingone on top of another.  Because fo the welding, the Arch is air tight and hollow inside.<p> 

The final piece -- the keystone -- was placed in October, 1965, and Bill Jackson was there. <p>

But the circumstances which surround the Arch placement are very interesting simply in themselves.<p>

<h4>Dedicating the Arch Easier Said than Done</h4>
The Mayor of St. Louis at that time wantsed to have a grand, public ceremony to commemorate the Arch's completion.  But Bill Jackson knew placing the keystone during the day would be difficult.  The heat of the sun on the Arch's southern exposure would cause half of it to expand and lean down a foot and a half.  <p>

In that case, the keystone wouldn't fit.<p>

"I told the Mayor that it would be best to place the last piece at two or three in the morning," Jackson says.   "But he wanted to hold a big political rally in the daytime."<p>

Jackson finally agreed to have the ceremony at nine in  the morning, on one condition: The Mayor would have every possible fire truck availavle in site to spray cool water on the southern base of the Arch.<p>

Even with this precaution and the assistance of several workers, it still took over three hous to insert the keytone.<p>

More than 25 years later, the Gateway Arch at St. Louis is the fourth most visited tourist attraction in the world and the most famous symbol of American growth.<p>

<center>
<h4>America's Potential for Growth Restrained by Government</h4>
</center>

Bill Jackson still has faith in America's potential.  But he believes exessive government regulation greatly reduces the potential for continued growth.<p>

"Our founders never expected government to bee as big as it is, " Jackson says.  "Government was only meant to be as big as necessary to protect us from foreign attack."<p>

"Right now the government is overly involved in the lives of the people," Jackson continues.  "Government isn't trying to help people work.  Instead, it makes them lazy.<p>

"The government wants to gain control of the people by trying to bring an end to free enterprise."<p>

Bill Jackson graduated from Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1930 with a deegree in Engineering and Business Administration.  He began working  at Pitt-Des Moines six years after he graduated and worked up the ladder, serving as Chairman of the Board of Pitt-Des Moines from1959 to 1990.  Now Jackson works mostly half days as Chairman Emeritus.<p>

He has been a generous supporter of Leadership Institute programs since 1999.<p>

<center>
<h4>Institute Educates Conservatives Who Share Jackson's Beliefs</h4>
</center>

"I like to see the number of conservatives grow in order to increase our salvation from liberal dominance," Jackson says.  "That is why I support the Leadership Institute, because they help these numbers grow. <p>

"I am encouraged to support the Leadership Institute because their educational programs teach young people how to go out and support conservative points of view which are so much better than liberal beliefs."<p>

Thanks to the generosity of donors like Bill Jackson, the Leadership Institute trains record numbers of young conservatives every year. <p>

These young advocates of free enterprise, limited government and traditional values will take up the banner of conervative leadership fo rmany years to come.<p><p>

[ <a href="i-bl.html">Contents</a> ]
<p><p>

<p><center><font size="-1">The Leadership Institute is a 501(c)(3) non-profit, non-partisan educational foundation.<br> It does not support, endorse or oppose candidates or proposed legislation.<br> All contributions to the Leadership Institute are tax deductible.<br></font></center></body>
