<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ABIC - Note about Senate Term Limits Vote</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<a href="/abic/top.map"><img src="/abic/images/top.gif" border="0" ALT="Americans Bac
k in Charge" ISMAP></a><p>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><H3>A Note About the Senate Term Limits Vote in April, 1996</H3></center>
<P>
In April, 1996, the Senate debated the Term Limits Constitutional Amendment.  During the days of April 19th, 22nd and 23rd, Senators took to the floor for a hearty discussion on the merits of the issue.  
<P>
Unfortunately, due to lack of Democratic support, the amendment never came to floor vote.  Instead, the Senate had a "cloture" vote which means they voted on whether to cut off debate so that the Senate could move forward to a full vote on the Amendment itself.  It takes 60 votes to cut off debate on any issue.  
<P>
On April 23rd, 1996, every single Republican Senator voted "yes" on cloture to go forward with the vote on the term limits amendment.  Because only five Democrats voted "yes", the cloture vote failed by a vote of 58-42.  The Senate was unable to cut off debate and therefore never voted on the actual amendment.
<P>
However, it is good to note that 58 Senators, a majority of the Senate, voted <EM>with</EM> term limits supporters.  While not all of these Senators may have voted "yes" on the actual amendment if it had come to a floor vote, this is nonetheless a great showing for the term limits issue in its first time at bat in the Senate.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<p>
<center>
