<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ABIC - Will Rogers and the 1920's Political Conventions</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<a href="/abic/top.map"><img src="/abic/images/top.gif" border="0" ALT="Americans Bac
k in Charge" ISMAP></a><p>
<P>
<BR><BR>
<CENTER><H3>Will Rogers and the 1920's Political Conventions - The Republicans</H3></CENTER>
<P>
<img src="/abic/images/rogers.jpg" align="left">
"Cowboy humorist" and star of stage and screen Will Rogers was commissioned to write 
about the 1920, 1924, 1928 and 1932 national political conventions, a job he thoroughly
enjoyed as these quadrennial politicalfests provided ample fodder for a humorist.  ABIC is pleased
 to offer just a sampling of Rogers' observations during the 1996 convention season.
  You'll note that in many cases things haven't changed much.  But in some cases 
things have changed so much that his statements offer even more ironic humor.
<P>
Each day we'll focus on a different aspect of the convention.  And as Rogers covered both
 the Democratic and Republican conventions, be sure to come back in two weeks and see 
what he had to say about the Democrats!
<P>
<h5>Click <a href="/abic/rogersbkgrd.html.cgi">here</a> for a little background on the 
1920's conventions and Will Rogers' writings.</h5>
<P>
Monday:  <a href="/abic/rogersmon.html.cgi">General Thoughts on the Convention, the Delegates</a><BR>
Tuesday: <a href="/abic/rogerstues.html.cgi">Platform, Parties and Issues</a><BR>
Wednesday: <a href="/abic/rogerswed.html.cgi">Vice-Presidential Nomination</a><BR>
Thursday: Presidential Nomination<BR>
Friday: Final Thoughts<BR>
<P><P>
<p>
<center><h3>The Presidential Nomination</h3></center>
<p>
1920
<ul><li>A week ago the Republicans thought they could win with anybody.  Now they can't find anybody they think they can win with.
<li>
I said: "This fellow Sproul you are for--nobody knows anything about him."  Pen said: "That's just what makes it so hard to nominate those other Republican candidates; people know too much about them."
<li>
(During the voting for the presidential nominee) Boies said: "I might just as well sent Connie Mack (grandfather of current Sen. Connie Mack, R-FL) out there.  He couldn't a finished any further back."
<li>
I said: "Do you think Johnson will start a third party?"  Boies said: "If he does this will be the most successful convention the Democrats ever held."
</ul><p>
1924
<ul><li>Things must be in a pretty bad way in the Republican Party when they have only Two Men who think they are good enough to run.  Why, in the Democratic Party they have a Thousand who think they are good enough.  According to that, they Democrats must have the most Able Party.
<li>
Lots of people can't understand the popularity that Mr. Coolidge is deservedly enjoying all over the country at the present time.  I can tell you.  It started the minute he opposed Congress and the Senate.  The People said: "If he is against Congress he must be right."  It was the surest fire political move anyone ever had a chance to make.  If he agreed with Congress he would have been as dead as they are today.
</ul><p>
<CENTER>***</CENTER>
<P>
Check back tomorrow (Friday) for a couple final thoughts from the inimitable Will Rogers.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<p>
