<html><head>
<TITLE>Dr. Larry P. Arnn</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<hr noshade>

   <A HREF = "../bios.htm">Return to Staff and Fellows</A> ||
   <A HREF = "../index.html">Claremont Institute Home Page</A>

   <hr noshade>

</center>

<P>

<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="images/arnn.jpg" hspace=15 vspace=15>

<BR>
<BR>

<center>

   <H1>Dr. Larry P. Arnn</H1>

</center>

<p>

Dr. Larry P. Arnn is President of the Claremont Institute, received his B.A. in Political Science and 
Accounting in 1974 from Arkansas State University.  He graduated with highest distinction.  He 
studied at the Claremont Graduate School and received his M.A. in Government in 1976 and his 
Ph.D. in Government in 1985.  His doctoral thesis is entitled "Winston Churchill as Minister of 
Munitions."  He studied in England from 1977 to 1980, first as a research student in International 
History at the London School of Economics and then in Modern History at Worcester College, 
Oxford University.

<p>

He has received numerous fellowships and awards, among them a two-year fellowship from 
the Alcoa Foundation in 1972; a Richard M. Weaver Fellowship in 1975; a Rotary International 
Fellowship in 1977; an Earhart Foundation Fellowship in 1978, 1979, and 1980; and a Winston 
S. Churchill Association Fellowship from 1977 to 1980.  

<p>

While in England, Dr. Arnn served as Director of Research for Mr. Martin Gilbert of Merton 
College, Oxford.  Mr. Gilbert is the Official Biographer of Sir Winston S. Churchill.  

<p>

Dr. Arnn was appointed by the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors to chair the Los 
Angeles County Bicentennial Commemoration Task Force in 1987.  His essay, "War and Peace 
in Winston Churchill" was included in Natural Right and Political Right, edited by Peter 
Schramm and Thomas Silver (Carolina Academic Press, 1985), and the essay "Principles and 
Phrases: Rhetoric in the Statesmanship of Winston S. Churchill" was published in Rhetoric and 
American Statesmanship, edited by Glen Thurow and Jeffrey Wallin (Carolina Academic Press, 
1984).

<p>

Dr. Arnn has published widely on political and economic subjects, especially housing policy, 
and government regulation of land use and transportation.  In March 1990, Dr. Arnn was 
appointed by HUD Secretary Jack Kemp to the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban 
Development Advisory Commission on Regulatory Barriers to Affordable Housing.

<p>

Dr. Arnn is the author of several studies on transportation and development in Southern 
California.  These include "Jobs Housing Balance: Too Good to Be True; Too Easy to Be Good" (The Claremont Institute, 1990); and "The No Growth Movement and the Transportation Crisis: 
The Bitter Legacy of Jerry Brown" (The Claremont Institute, 1989); and "In Defense of Red 
Tape," an essay on the first year of the Clinton administration, in <i>Consequences of the Clinton 
Victory</i> (Ashbrook Press, 1994).

<p>

Dr. Arnn is married to the former Penelope Houghton of Preston, England, and has three 
young children, Henry, Katy, and Alice.  The Arnns reside in Claremont, California.  

<P>

