<html><head>
<title>Moral Ideas in America, 1st Amendment</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<center>
<table border=0 width=85%><tr><td>

<hr size=4 align=center>

<center>
<h1>Moral Ideas for America</h1>
</center>

<blockquote>
"There is no truth more thoroughly established, than that 
there exists in the economy and course of nature, an 
indissoluble union between virtue and happiness. . . ."
<DD> -- President George Washington
</blockquote>

<P>
<a name = "porno">
<hr size=4 align=center>
<P>

<center>
<h2>The First Amendment and Pornography</h2>
<h3>Francis Canavan</h3>
</center>

The clause of the First Amendment that is relevant to the subject of 
pornography is:  "Congress shall make no law . . . abridging the 
freedom of speech or of the press."  The Supreme Court, through its 
interpretation of the Fourteenth Amendment, has applied this clause to 
state and local governments, so that all levels of government in this 
country are bound by it.  The question before us now is, what is this 
freedom of speech or of the press that is protected by the Amendment?
I am not going to argue that the Supreme Court has spoken, that the 
matter is settled, that there is nothing more to discuss, and that those 
who disagree with me should therefore shut up.  I leave that kind of 
argument to people on the other side.  But I will occasionally cite 
Supreme Court decisions, because I want to show that the Supreme 
Court has occasionally said things that support my case.
<P>

Indeed, contrary to common opinion, the Court has never actually 
banned any and all regulation of freedom of speech and press.  I feel 
safe in saying that it has never subscribed to the view that freedom of 
speech is absolute-or that obscenity as such is protected by it.  
<P>

For example, in 1961, in the case of Konigsberg v. State Bar of 
California, the Court held that "constitutionally protected freedom of 
speech is narrower than an unlimited license to talk."  In a footnote it 
pointed out that any contrary view "cannot be reconciled with the law 
relating to libel, slander, misrepresentation, obscenity, perjury, false 
advertising, solicitation of crime, complicity by encouragement, 
conspiracy and the like." 
<P>

The other point of view, against which I stand, is what I will call the 
absolutist view of freedom of speech and press-a view that is 
sometimes called "First Amendment fundamentalism."  This was 
represented on the Supreme Court by Justices Black and Douglas in 
their day.  According to them, the only line that can be drawn legally or 
constitutionally is between speech and conduct.  If it is speech, it is 
protected absolutely.  If it becomes conduct, then the state can regulate 
it.  For all practical purposes, Justices Brennan and Marshall later sub-
scribed to the same view.  That is to say, they approached it without 
ever quite reaching it.  But it was effectively the same.  
<P>

Whether among people on the Court or off it, this absolutist school 
of thought has telescoped freedom of speech and press into "freedom 
of expression."  "Expression" started out as a sort of shorthand way of 
referring to speech and press, but now covers things that are 
neither-like what the Court has described as "nonobscene nude 
dancing."  When you get to that point, it doesn't matter what is 
expressed or how it is expressed, so long as it is expressed rather than 
done.  The fact of expression is all that really matters.  Thus expression 
is detached from any public or societal purpose that it is supposed to 
serve.  Expression becomes its own end and its own justification.  
Therefore there can be no constitutional limit on it.  That is what I call 
the absolutist view.  
<P>

I am advancing an opposite position which holds that a rational 
interpretation of the constitutional freedom of speech and press must 
consider the purposes which that freedom is intended to serve.  And 
that in any given case coming before the courts, it must be asked 
whether the particular speech or publication or expression in question 
has any discernible relation to those purposes.  Why?  Because the end 
or purpose of the free speech and free press guarantee-or indeed of any 
legal or constitutional right-is the rationale or the principle that justifies 
it. 
<P>

<center>
<h3>Rights Have Purposes, Hence Limits</h3>
</center>

We do not legally recognize or create rights for no purpose 
whatsoever.  We have in each instance something that we wish to 
achieve.  Once we admit this, and admit that the constitutional 
guarantee of freedom of speech and press has a purpose or purposes, 
we have also accepted the principle that limits it.
<P>

In addition to justifying the guarantee, the purpose indicates what 
the limits are; if a particular expression has little or no discernible 
relation to the purpose of the First Amendment guarantee, or, even 
more, if it positively impedes that purpose, then it is not protected by 
the guarantee.  
<P>

The Supreme Court in 1942 made a statement which, I think, is still 
valid today, in deciding the case of Chaplinsky v. New Hampshire:
<P>

<blockquote>
There are certain well-defined and narrowly limited 
classes of speech, the prevention and punishment of which 
have never been thought to raise any constitutional 
problems.  These include the lewd and obscene, the 
profane, the libelous, and the insulting or "fighting" 
words-those which by their very utterance inflict injury or 
tend to incite an immediate breach of the peace.  It has 
been well observed that such utterances are no essential 
part of any exposition of ideas and are of such slight social 
value as a step to truth that any benefit that may be derived 
from them is clearly outweighed by the social interest in 
order and morality. 
</blockquote>

<P>
Notice, this says that the First Amendment guarantee has a 
purpose-the search for truth-against which one can weigh a particular 
utterance; and also that if one finds this utterance has little or no role in 
this search, or in the exposition of ideas, then it can be outweighed by 
the social interest in morality.
<P>

Of course, one will not find in the Supreme Court's opinions 
anywhere a catalogue of all the purposes of the First Amendment in a 
hierarchical arrangement.  Nor will one find a catalogue of the social 
interests that can outweigh them.  But there are plenty of statements 
indicating that the Court does recognize (however reluctantly) that 
some kinds of speech are more important than others, that some are 
pretty unimportant, and that some are simply off the scale and not 
protected at all.
<P>

In other words, the social interest that justifies limiting or even pro-
hibiting low kinds of speech need not be great.  When dealing with a 
high kind of speech, on the other hand, we have to weigh in something 
as important as the national security in order to justify any sort of 
limitation.
<P>

So the freedoms of speech and press are defined by goals.  They are 
broad but not unlimited.  The principal goal of these freedoms is to 
furnish a necessary condition for running a representative, democratic 
form of government.  Clearly, there can't be a democracy where people 
can't talk or write about politics, or campaign for or against candidates 
or tickets or policies.  More broadly, as has been said over and over 
again-not only in the opinions of the Supreme Court, but in the whole 
tradition of defending free speech and press going back to John 
Milton's Areopagitica-the purpose of this freedom is the pursuit of 
truth or-to use a phrase of which the Court is fond-the establishment of 
"a free marketplace of ideas," in which truth may emerge.  We should 
note in this context, and emphasize the fact, that the free speech and 
press clause presupposes or is founded upon a faith in human reason, as 
the Court has often said.
<P>

I think that one could stretch this a bit further and say that the 
purpose of the First Amendment is to provide people, through open 
discussion and through works of literature and art, with the opportunity 
to explore not only what is true, but also what is good and what is 
beautiful.  Nonetheless, all of these forms of expression are subject to 
rational judgment.

<center>
<h3>Drawing the Line</h3>
</center>

It may be true that works of literature and art are primarily appeals 
to the imagination and to emotion rather than to reason.  I don't quite 
agree with that opinion, because I think it relies upon a very narrow 
conception of reason.  But let's assume that it's true:  Even if a work of 
literature or art is primarily an appeal to imagination and to emotion, 
nonetheless, reason can judge what emotion is being appealed to.  We 
can look at an alleged work of art and determine whether it appeals to a 
love of beauty, to the appreciation of human good and evil, to the 
vicarious enjoyment of adventure, to the desire for a good belly laugh, 
to sexual lust, or to a sick appetite for violence.  
<P>

I am suggesting here that there are various levels and kinds of 
speech, and that reason can make judgments that distinguish them.  The 
Supreme Court, I think, agreed with this in the 1957 case of Roth v. 
U.S., when it laid down a norm for judging what is legally obscene-and 
thus constitutionally unprotected.  The test is "whether to the average 
person, applying contemporary community standards, the dominant 
theme of the material taken as a whole appeals to prurient interest."   
Clearly the court assumes here that the average person can judge 
this, at least in the case where the appeal to prurient interest goes far 
enough.  There will always be borderline cases; in these we should 
favor freedom.  But sometimes there isn't any real doubt.  
<P>

In 1973, in Miller v. California, the Supreme Court said that courts 
can distinguish commerce in ideas, which is protected by the First 
Amendment, from commercial exploitation of obscene material.  
Indeed, it went on to say, courts must make this distinction, because "to 
equate the free and robust exchange of ideas and political debate with 
commercial exploitation of obscene material demeans the grand 
conception of the First Amendment and its high purposes."   So, then, 
there are purposes in the First Amendment, and some of them, at least, 
are high.  The First Amendment doesn't protect all speech simply 
because it is speech, any more than freedom protects all action simply 
because it is action.  We must always ask, what kind of action?  Who is 
doing what?  And-as they say-to whom?
<P>

In a companion case, decided the same day as Miller v. California, 
the Court held that legislatures as well as courts can distinguish 
between protected and unprotected expression:
<P>

<blockquote>
The sum of experience affords an ample basis for legisla-
tures to conclude that a sensitive, key relationship of hu-
man existence, central to family life, community welfare, 
and the development of human personality, can be 
debased and distorted by crass commercial exploitation of 
sex. 
</blockquote>

<P>
Furthermore-and this is very important-the Court said: "Nothing in 
the Constitution prohibits a State from reaching such a conclusion and 
acting on it legislatively simply because there is no conclusive 
evidence or empirical data."   After all, the Court pointed out, 
legislatures have acted in many fields on indemonstrable premises, yet 
the Supreme Court has upheld their legislation.
<P>

It is utter flimflammery to insist that we have to get social scientists 
to prove that, for instance, pornography does harm.  Independently of 
any proof of harm that certain types of expression do, we can recognize 
these types as being at best worthless, and therefore not worth 
protecting.  Any rational ground for thinking that they do some harm is 
sufficient for prohibiting them.  

<center>
<h3>Answering the Absolutists</h3>
</center>

Needless to say, there is an absolutist response to all this, which it 
seems to me is reducible to two arguments.  The first is what I call the 
"pearl in the garage" argument, the argument that every expression, as 
long as it is an expression, contains (or at least may for all we know 
contain) something of value of which society would not be deprived; 
and that we should be willing to wade through an ocean of garbage to 
find it.  
<P>

I believe it is an adequate answer to this remarkable argument to 
say: "We know there is an ocean of garbage, but we do not know that 
there is a pearl in it; and even if there is a pearl, we do not know that it 
is a pearl of such great price that it is worth wading through an ocean 
of garbage to get it.  Nor do we know that we have to wade through 
this ocean of garbage to find this particular pearl, for it may be a 
thought that occurred to somebody else who was able to express it 
without burying it in an ocean of garbage."
<P>

Faced with this line of reasoning, the absolutists tend to fall back 
upon the argument of John Stuart Mill in his essay On Liberty.  The 
risks involved in allowing any limitation of expression are always 
greater than the risks involved in guaranteeing an unlimited freedom of 
speech.  To guarantee an absolutely unlimited freedom of expression 
will doubtless result in some harm, but it will always be less harm than 
is done by allowing any limitation at all upon expression.   
<P>

To hold this view requires an ideological, doctrinaire mentality-a 
mentality for which the needle on the gauge always stands either at 
zero degrees or at 180 degrees.  Yet I submit that legislation-a balance, 
as Edmund Burke said, sometimes between good and good, sometimes 
between good and evil, and sometimes even between evil and 
evil-practically always corresponds with one of the 179 degrees 
between zero and 180.
<P>

It is only the doctrinaire mentality that can insist we either 
guarantee Fanny Hill or else join the Spanish Inquisition, there being 
no middle ground.  Or that if we ban the raunchiest of X-rated films, 
we will undoubtedly end up banning Shakespeare and the Bible.  Or, as 
one noted civil libertarian has suggested, that if we allow any limitation 
whatsoever on freedom of expression, we will end up burning witches, 
as they did in 17th-century Massachusetts.
<P>

There is no reason to accept these arguments.  The whole history of 
literature contradicts them.  Take, for example, the names of 
Shakespeare, Dante, Cervantes, Moliere, Goethe, and Dostoyevsky.  
Not one of these writers lived in a regime of unlimited freedom of 
expression.  Not one of them, for that matter, lived in a liberal 
democracy.  And yet critics have compared their writings favorably 
with the very best work of Ernest Hemingway and Norman Mailer.  
Consider the history of our own country.  A regime of unlimited 
freedom of expression came in only in the 1960s.  Do we know, or 
have we any reason to believe, that American arts and letters were 
stifled before that time?  Or that we are producing better arts and letters 
today than we did prior to 1965?
<P>

I can remember when Fiorello La Guardia was the mayor of New 
York, and drove the burlesque shows and the striptease joints out of the 
city.  He simply refused to renew their licenses, and they didn't come 
back until after John Lindsay was elected mayor in 1965.  Yet the La 
Guardia years were the golden years of the Broadway musical, the 
years when we had the great shows-Oklahoma, South Pacific, The King 
and I, My Fair Lady, and so forth.  There is no ground on which 
anyone can prove that banning pornography harmed Broadway.  And I 
would say that that's true of literature generally.
<P>

All of these absolutist arguments rest upon a profound mistrust of 
the ability of average human beings to make prudent practical 
judgments.  Granted, if we let the public decide, sometimes it will go 
too far and will be too restrictive.  Sometimes.  But there is nothing that 
gives us any reason to believe that the American public is a bunch of 
frustrated Puritans held back only by the strong arm of the American 
Civil Liberties Union.
<P>

Furthermore, I think the type of arguments that are used for 
absolute freedom of speech and press undermine these freedoms in the 
long run.  Absolutists say that we have no standards by which we can 
distinguish the purposes of expression, or judge what kinds of 
expression-however coarse they may be-make at least some 
contribution to our progress.  But if we go far enough along that line, 
we will wind up wondering why the freedoms of speech and press are 
worth protecting at all.  As Walter Lippmann wrote in The Public 
Philosophy, "freedom to speak and think are not self-evident 
necessities.  It is only from the hope and the intention of discovering 
truth that freedom acquires such high public significance."  But, he 
warned, 
<P>

<blockquote>
when the chaff of silliness, baseness, and deception is so 
voluminous that it submerges the kernels of truth, freedom 
of speech may produce such frivolity, or such mischief, 
that it cannot be preserved against the demand for a 
restoration of order or of decency.  If there is a dividing 
line between liberty and license, it is where freedom of 
speech is no longer respected as a procedure of the truth 
and becomes the unrestricted right to exploit the ignorance, and to incite the passions, of the people  Then freedom is such a hullabaloo of sophistry, propaganda, special 
pleading, lobbying, and salesmanship that it is difficult to 
remember why freedom of speech is worth the pain and 
trouble of defending it.
</blockquote>

<center>
<h3>Practical Steps Against Pornography</h3>
</center>

So far I have argued only that the First Amendment does not bar all 
regulation of expression, and that obscenity is not constitutionally 
protected.  The practical question of what kind of regulation citizens 
can advocate with any hope of having it accepted is a more difficult 
one.  Such citizen-advocates are up against a deep-seated prejudice in 
the minds of many Americans, who may not know much about the 
Constitution, but are convinced that the First Amendment guarantees 
everyone's absolute right to say, hear, read, and view whatever he 
pleases.  This conviction has been fostered in their minds by liberal 
academics, journalists, and entertainers, all of whom have an obvious 
interest in it.  It is now the prevailing orthodoxy in the law schools, and 
has heavily influenced the courts.
<P>

The odds are therefore against the success of efforts to restrict the 
production and dissemination of pornography, but they are not 
hopelessly great.  Concerned citizens should make such efforts, but 
with care and caution.  The first piece of advice that I would offer is: 
don't go for the gold.  Do not seek sweeping pieces of legislation that 
ban everything that someone finds pornographic.  Begin with the hard-
core stuff that is clearly pornographic.  
<P>

On the other hand, the purpose should be to ban the sale of 
pornography, not merely to keep porn shops and movie houses a 
certain distance from schools and churches.  If the freedom of speech 
absolutists fear that they may not be able to prevent some restriction of 
pornography, they will offer that sort of "compromise."  It should not 
be accepted!  Acceptance would imply that pornography, no matter 
how raw, is protected by the First Amendment and is, at most, subject 
to regulation of where it may be sold.  
<P>

A proposed ordinance offered to a city council or state legislature 
should clearly specify what it intends to prohibit, in language that the 
courts will find hard to declare unconstitutional on the ground that it is 
"vague and overbroad."  The courts hold, reasonably enough, that the 
law may not punish a man for violating the law, when it did not tell 
him clearly what it forbade him to do.  Some judges, of course, will 
find any law vague and overbroad that puts any limits on "expression," 
but we should not play into their hands by using loose legal language.
<P>

A proposed ordinance should also be accompanied by a well-
thought out statement of reasons for restricting the sale of this kind of 
pornography.  It need not and should not seek to prove that 
pornography has done direct, tangible, assignable harm to individuals, 
or has been the cause of crimes committed by particular persons.  A 
rational case, however, which abstains from off-putting moralistic 
language, can be made for the connection between the material sought 
to be banned and harm to society, along the lines of Miller v. 
California.  This case will support the constitutionality of the proposed 
legislation.  
<P>

Finally, the citizen group or groups sponsoring the legislation will 
have to take steps to arouse public opinion and win public support for 
the ordinance.  That will require a certain amount of leg work.  
If that sounds like a big order, well, it is.  But it can be done by 
dedicated people who are willing to put time, effort and money into it.  
They should seek advice from organizations that have long been active 
in the fight against pornography and know what can succeed and what 
will likely fail.  Among such organizations are:
<P>

<blockquote>
American Family Association<BR>
P.O. Box 2440<BR>
Tupelo, MS  38803 <BR>
tel. (800) 326-4543<BR>
<P>

Morality in Media, Inc. <BR>
475 Riverside Dr. <BR>
New York, NY  10115  <BR>
tel. (212) 870-3222<BR>
<P>

National Coalition Against Pornography<BR>
800 Compton Road, Suite 9224<BR>
Cincinnati, OH  45231  <BR>
tel. (513) 521-6227<BR>
<P>

National Family Legal Foundation<BR>
5353 North 16th St., Suite 400<BR>
Phoenix, AZ  85016  <BR>
tel. (602) 265-1513<BR>
</blockquote>

<P>
If possible, the proponents of an anti-pornography ordinance should 
ask the help of a good lawyer who is on their side and believes in their 
cause-perhaps a friendly law school professor who is well versed in the 
constitutional law of speech and press.  
<P>

The citizen group, therefore, should survey the field, seek advice on 
where to get the kind of lawyer or lawyers that it needs, and carefully 
choose the place in which to seek the desired legislation.  It would not 
be wise to begin with New York or San Francisco.  Better to pick a city 
or a state where victory is possible, and the local courts are likely to 
sustain the legislation.  From that point on, as George Washington said 
in his Farewell Address, let us raise a standard to which the wise and 
the good may repair; the event is in the hands of God.

<P>
<hr size=4 align=center>
